1
01:00:52,807 --> 01:00:55,644
[soft eerie music playing]

2
01:01:34,416 --> 01:01:37,119
<i>My name is Alithea.</i>

3
01:01:37,153 --> 01:01:39,754
<i>My story is true.</i>

4
01:01:39,788 --> 01:01:42,190
<i>You're more likely
to believe me, however,</i>

5
01:01:42,223 --> 01:01:44,559
<i>if I tell it as a fairy tale.</i>

6
01:01:47,063 --> 01:01:49,698
<i>So, once upon a time,</i>

7
01:01:49,731 --> 01:01:53,635
<i>when humans hurtled
across the sky on metal wings,</i>

8
01:01:54,369 --> 01:01:55,570
<i>when they wore webbed feet</i>

9
01:01:55,603 --> 01:01:58,273
<i>and walked
on the bottom of the sea,</i>

10
01:01:59,407 --> 01:02:01,543
<i>when they held
in their hands glass tiles</i>

11
01:02:01,576 --> 01:02:04,080
<i>that could coax
love songs from the air...</i>

12
01:02:04,113 --> 01:02:05,447
[music playing
through headphones]

13
01:02:05,480 --> 01:02:08,983
<i>...there was a woman,
adequately happy and alone.</i>

14
01:02:09,951 --> 01:02:11,619
<i>Alone by choice.</i>

15
01:02:11,653 --> 01:02:14,522
<i>Happy because
she was independent,</i>

16
01:02:14,556 --> 01:02:17,792
<i>living off the exercise
of her scholarly mind.</i>

17
01:02:19,961 --> 01:02:21,529
<i>Her business was story.</i>

18
01:02:22,864 --> 01:02:24,399
<i>She was a narratologist</i>

19
01:02:24,432 --> 01:02:26,168
<i>who sought to find the truths</i>

20
01:02:26,202 --> 01:02:29,304
<i>common to all the stories
of humankind.</i>

21
01:02:30,405 --> 01:02:33,241
<i>To this end,
once or twice a year,</i>

22
01:02:33,274 --> 01:02:36,011
<i>she ventured to strange lands.</i>

23
01:02:36,045 --> 01:02:38,580
<i>To China, the South Seas,</i>

24
01:02:38,613 --> 01:02:40,949
<i>and the timeless cities
of the Levant...</i>

25
01:02:44,819 --> 01:02:49,524
<i>where her kind gathered
to tell stories about stories.</i>

26
01:02:52,027 --> 01:02:53,195
[man 1] This way.

27
01:02:53,229 --> 01:02:54,939
- [Alithea] Excuse me.
- [man 1] This way, lady.

28
01:02:54,963 --> 01:02:56,998
What are you doing?
Can you let go, please?

29
01:02:57,032 --> 01:02:59,235
The mysteries of Istanbul.

30
01:02:59,267 --> 01:03:01,436
[static buzzing]

31
01:03:01,469 --> 01:03:03,471
- [man 2] Alithea!
- [man 1 grunts]

32
01:03:03,905 --> 01:03:05,040
Alithea!

33
01:03:10,045 --> 01:03:11,479
Welcome!

34
01:03:11,513 --> 01:03:13,182
- Welcome at last! Aw.
- Gunhan!

35
01:03:13,215 --> 01:03:15,316
- [both laugh]
- My dear friend.

36
01:03:15,350 --> 01:03:16,961
- [Alithea] Oh, how wonderful!
- [Gunhan] I'm sorry.

37
01:03:16,985 --> 01:03:18,486
- This is Amina.
- Amina.

38
01:03:18,520 --> 01:03:20,421
From the British Council.

39
01:03:21,856 --> 01:03:24,626
That fellow at the airport
manhandling my luggage,

40
01:03:24,659 --> 01:03:25,860
did you see him?

41
01:03:25,894 --> 01:03:27,029
What fellow?

42
01:03:28,329 --> 01:03:30,799
He scuttled off
when you arrived.

43
01:03:31,633 --> 01:03:36,038
Small, sheepskin jacket,
pink collar.

44
01:03:38,673 --> 01:03:39,774
Interesting.

45
01:03:40,809 --> 01:03:42,977
He was hot to touch.

46
01:03:44,146 --> 01:03:45,413
Musky.

47
01:03:45,980 --> 01:03:47,448
Perhaps he was a djinn.

48
01:03:47,482 --> 01:03:50,119
An illegal taxi driver,
more likely.

49
01:03:50,152 --> 01:03:52,087
Wearing too much cologne.

50
01:03:52,121 --> 01:03:53,755
So, Professor,

51
01:03:53,788 --> 01:03:56,091
you saying you believe in djinn?

52
01:03:56,125 --> 01:03:59,195
I believe there are those
who need to believe in them.

53
01:03:59,228 --> 01:04:00,361
Including me?

54
01:04:00,395 --> 01:04:01,896
Djinn, ghosts,

55
01:04:02,597 --> 01:04:04,699
aliens, whatever helps.

56
01:04:07,468 --> 01:04:09,004
[Gunhan laughs]

57
01:04:10,939 --> 01:04:13,842
The hotel's arranged
a lovely surprise for you.

58
01:04:19,181 --> 01:04:21,016
It's the Agatha Christie room.

59
01:04:21,050 --> 01:04:21,950
In this room,

60
01:04:21,983 --> 01:04:24,919
she wrote
<i>Murder on the Orient Express.</i>

61
01:04:29,624 --> 01:04:30,859
[sighs]

62
01:04:30,892 --> 01:04:32,894
[audience laughing]

63
01:04:32,927 --> 01:04:34,796
[Gunhan chuckles]

64
01:04:34,829 --> 01:04:37,565
[Gunhan] So,
how would you explain

65
01:04:37,599 --> 01:04:40,135
the power of a thunderstorm

66
01:04:40,169 --> 01:04:41,337
if you don't have the means

67
01:04:41,369 --> 01:04:43,972
to measure and model
meteorological data?

68
01:04:45,607 --> 01:04:47,742
How can you explain the seasons?

69
01:04:47,775 --> 01:04:50,545
Autumn through winter
to spring and summer,

70
01:04:50,578 --> 01:04:52,714
if you don't know that the Earth

71
01:04:52,747 --> 01:04:55,516
orbits the Sun
while tilted on an axis?

72
01:04:56,584 --> 01:04:58,620
Everything was mystery.

73
01:04:58,653 --> 01:05:03,691
The seasons, tsunamis,
microbial disease...

74
01:05:03,725 --> 01:05:07,795
What else could we do
but resort to stories?

75
01:05:07,829 --> 01:05:11,033
As Dr. Binnie has
encouraged us to understand,

76
01:05:11,066 --> 01:05:12,934
stories were once the only way

77
01:05:12,967 --> 01:05:15,503
to make our bewildering
existence coherent.

78
01:05:15,536 --> 01:05:17,273
That's exactly right.

79
01:05:17,306 --> 01:05:20,175
We gave name
to the unknown forces

80
01:05:20,209 --> 01:05:23,212
behind all wonder
and catastrophe,

81
01:05:23,245 --> 01:05:25,580
by telling each other...

82
01:05:28,850 --> 01:05:31,853
By telling each other stories.

83
01:05:31,886 --> 01:05:33,655
- [Gunhan] let me show you.
- [static buzzes]

84
01:05:33,688 --> 01:05:38,227
We told tales of specific,
powerful, relatable gods

85
01:05:38,260 --> 01:05:41,796
ever present in all cultures,
in all mythologies,

86
01:05:41,829 --> 01:05:45,034
from the Greeks,
to the Romans, to the Norse,

87
01:05:45,067 --> 01:05:46,701
and so on, and so on.

88
01:05:46,734 --> 01:05:50,239
The familiar descendant
of Zeus, Poseidon, Athena,

89
01:05:50,272 --> 01:05:52,640
Thor, the whole gang,

90
01:05:52,674 --> 01:05:55,277
find expression even today.

91
01:05:55,311 --> 01:05:56,778
[low electrical humming]

92
01:05:56,811 --> 01:05:59,747
These are their vestiges.

93
01:06:01,417 --> 01:06:04,919
The question remains,
what is their purpose?

94
01:06:07,356 --> 01:06:10,359
[electrical humming continues]

95
01:06:10,392 --> 01:06:12,460
What do we require of them now?

96
01:06:14,529 --> 01:06:17,665
There is mythos,
and there is science.

97
01:06:17,699 --> 01:06:19,600
[electrical humming stops]

98
01:06:19,634 --> 01:06:22,271
[Alithea softly] Oh. Sorry.

99
01:06:22,304 --> 01:06:26,574
Mythology is what
we knew back then.

100
01:06:26,607 --> 01:06:29,711
Science is what we know so far.

101
01:06:29,744 --> 01:06:32,047
[low electrical humming resumes]

102
01:06:34,383 --> 01:06:36,718
Sooner or later,

103
01:06:36,751 --> 01:06:39,554
our creation stories
are replaced

104
01:06:39,587 --> 01:06:41,622
by the narratives of science.

105
01:06:42,490 --> 01:06:45,060
Painstaking science.

106
01:06:45,094 --> 01:06:46,995
And all gods and monsters

107
01:06:47,895 --> 01:06:50,165
outlive their original purpose

108
01:06:51,266 --> 01:06:53,534
and are reduced to metaphor.

109
01:06:53,568 --> 01:06:55,837
Rubbish! [Roars]

110
01:06:58,573 --> 01:07:00,242
[Gunhan muffled] Alithea!

111
01:07:00,275 --> 01:07:02,011
[woman speaking indistinctly]

112
01:07:04,346 --> 01:07:05,613
[Gunhan] Alithea.

113
01:07:06,514 --> 01:07:07,682
[woman] What happened?

114
01:07:07,715 --> 01:07:09,284
[Gunhan] I don't know.
She just fell.

115
01:07:09,318 --> 01:07:11,220
- She just fell.
- [Amina grunts]

116
01:07:11,253 --> 01:07:13,222
[Amina] Gosh. [Exclaiming]

117
01:07:20,162 --> 01:07:21,596
[Gunhan] Are you okay?

118
01:07:22,097 --> 01:07:24,266
[audience clapping]

119
01:07:29,238 --> 01:07:30,772
[rattling]

120
01:07:32,041 --> 01:07:33,475
[Gunhan] Shouldn't
you see a doctor?

121
01:07:33,509 --> 01:07:34,986
[Alithea] Why?
When I feel so well?

122
01:07:35,010 --> 01:07:37,246
[Gunhan] Forgive me, Alithea.
Are you sure?

123
01:07:37,279 --> 01:07:39,680
[Alithea] Apart from
the usual aches and pains,

124
01:07:39,714 --> 01:07:41,383
there is nothing untoward.

125
01:07:41,417 --> 01:07:43,085
There's no reason
to make a fuss.

126
01:07:43,118 --> 01:07:45,120
[Gunhan] So, what happened
back there?

127
01:07:49,058 --> 01:07:53,095
Lately, my imagination's
been getting the better of me.

128
01:07:53,694 --> 01:07:55,663
Ambushing me.

129
01:07:55,696 --> 01:07:57,032
I think it's a warning.

130
01:07:57,066 --> 01:07:58,267
About what?

131
01:07:59,567 --> 01:08:01,569
Not to be complacent.

132
01:08:01,602 --> 01:08:03,905
To keep on my toes.

133
01:08:03,938 --> 01:08:06,574
It manifests rudely
from time to time.

134
01:08:06,607 --> 01:08:09,111
I try not to fight it off.

135
01:08:09,144 --> 01:08:13,148
It takes charge for a moment,
and then it steps back.

136
01:08:13,182 --> 01:08:14,516
What steps back?

137
01:08:14,550 --> 01:08:17,752
Oh, Gunhan, it's
irrational. Pay it no mind.

138
01:08:20,055 --> 01:08:22,458
[Gunhan] You are behaving like
a child. Do you know that?

139
01:08:22,491 --> 01:08:24,135
[Alithea] You know,
I am actually a child.

140
01:08:24,159 --> 01:08:25,494
[Gunhan laughs]

141
01:08:25,527 --> 01:08:28,197
[people chattering indistinctly]

142
01:08:28,230 --> 01:08:31,266
[Alithea] <i>If there is fate,</i>
<i>can we escape it?</i>

143
01:08:32,034 --> 01:08:33,302
<i>Who can say?</i>

144
01:08:33,835 --> 01:08:35,970
<i>But I tell you this,</i>

145
01:08:36,004 --> 01:08:38,173
<i>in the Grand Bazaar of Istanbul,</i>

146
01:08:38,207 --> 01:08:43,078
<i>there are 62 streets
and 4,000 shops.</i>

147
01:08:43,112 --> 01:08:46,381
<i>And in one of those shops,
there are three rooms.</i>

148
01:08:47,516 --> 01:08:49,151
<i>In the smallest of those rooms,</i>

149
01:08:49,184 --> 01:08:51,986
<i>there was a pile
of things unsorted,</i>

150
01:08:52,020 --> 01:08:53,654
<i>old and new.</i>

151
01:08:54,523 --> 01:08:56,657
<i>From the bottom of that pile,</i>

152
01:08:57,493 --> 01:08:59,228
<i>I chose a memento.</i>

153
01:09:05,167 --> 01:09:06,767
Do you know what this is?

154
01:09:06,801 --> 01:09:09,670
I'm not sure,
but it could be Cesm-i Bulbul,

155
01:09:09,704 --> 01:09:11,140
a "Nightingale's Eye."

156
01:09:11,173 --> 01:09:14,343
Around 1845, there were
these glassmakers in Incirkoy.

157
01:09:14,376 --> 01:09:17,346
They were famous for this
spiral blue-white pattern.

158
01:09:17,379 --> 01:09:19,381
Oh, please.
It's a gift from me.

159
01:09:19,414 --> 01:09:21,216
Choose something less forlorn.

160
01:09:24,520 --> 01:09:28,257
And, uh, if this
is Cesm-i Bulbul,

161
01:09:28,290 --> 01:09:30,791
uh, is there a way
of authenticating it?

162
01:09:30,825 --> 01:09:32,528
Well, they say
that if it is genuine,

163
01:09:32,561 --> 01:09:34,563
sometimes you can see
specks of blood

164
01:09:34,596 --> 01:09:35,997
from the lungs
of the glassblowers.

165
01:09:36,031 --> 01:09:39,201
But this is more likely
a recent imitation.

166
01:09:39,234 --> 01:09:42,104
It's been damaged by fire.
Pick something else.

167
01:09:42,770 --> 01:09:44,406
No, thank you, Gunhan.

168
01:09:45,340 --> 01:09:46,674
I like it.

169
01:09:46,707 --> 01:09:49,677
Whatever it is, I'm sure
it has an interesting story.

170
01:10:05,394 --> 01:10:07,762
[telephone ringing]

171
01:10:16,238 --> 01:10:17,072
Hello?

172
01:10:17,105 --> 01:10:18,149
[man] <i>Good morning, Dr. Binnie.</i>

173
01:10:18,173 --> 01:10:19,874
- Good morning.
<i>- This is room service.</i>

174
01:10:19,907 --> 01:10:21,276
- Yes.
<i>- How do you like your eggs?</i>

175
01:10:21,310 --> 01:10:22,644
Er, runny, please.

176
01:10:22,678 --> 01:10:25,013
<i>- And with toast?</i>
- Yes, but no crusts.

177
01:10:25,047 --> 01:10:27,182
<i>- Two eggs?</i>
- Just one.

178
01:10:27,216 --> 01:10:29,117
<i>- Okay, thank you.</i>
- Thank you.

179
01:10:52,907 --> 01:10:54,875
[electric toothbrush whirring]

180
01:10:56,811 --> 01:10:58,513
[bottle rattling]

181
01:10:59,880 --> 01:11:02,150
[bottle rattling intensifying]

182
01:11:02,184 --> 01:11:03,218
[gasps]

183
01:11:07,389 --> 01:11:08,756
[gasps]

184
01:11:13,328 --> 01:11:14,829
[toothbrush clatters]

185
01:11:16,732 --> 01:11:19,268
[squelching]

186
01:11:37,352 --> 01:11:39,121
[rustling]

187
01:11:45,727 --> 01:11:48,497
[squelching]

188
01:11:48,530 --> 01:11:49,631
[creature breaths heavily]

189
01:11:49,665 --> 01:11:51,433
[squeaks]

190
01:11:54,069 --> 01:11:58,206
[creature breathing heavily]

191
01:11:58,240 --> 01:12:02,910
I'm going to close my eyes
and count to three,

192
01:12:02,943 --> 01:12:04,446
after which I would be grateful

193
01:12:04,479 --> 01:12:05,913
if you would be gone.

194
01:12:09,217 --> 01:12:10,719
One,

195
01:12:10,752 --> 01:12:12,120
two,

196
01:12:12,820 --> 01:12:14,289
three.

197
01:12:14,323 --> 01:12:17,025
[breathing continues]

198
01:12:18,826 --> 01:12:20,595
Four,

199
01:12:20,629 --> 01:12:21,929
five,

200
01:12:23,065 --> 01:12:24,466
six,

201
01:12:24,499 --> 01:12:26,535
seven, eight,

202
01:12:26,568 --> 01:12:28,103
nine, ten.

203
01:12:30,639 --> 01:12:33,508
[creature grunting softly]

204
01:12:33,542 --> 01:12:36,011
[growling softly]

205
01:12:41,216 --> 01:12:44,119
[creature speaking indistinctly]

206
01:12:49,157 --> 01:12:51,560
I don't suppose
you speak English?

207
01:12:51,593 --> 01:12:53,195
[creature speaking
ancient Greek]

208
01:12:53,228 --> 01:12:54,329
<i>Deutsch?</i>

209
01:12:55,364 --> 01:12:56,631
<i>Espanol?</i>

210
01:12:57,566 --> 01:12:58,600
<i>Ellinika?</i>

211
01:12:58,633 --> 01:13:00,168
[creature grunts]

212
01:13:02,204 --> 01:13:04,939
[creature speaking
ancient Greek]

213
01:13:06,808 --> 01:13:09,511
[in ancient Greek]

214
01:13:11,713 --> 01:13:13,914
[creature speaking]

215
01:13:40,876 --> 01:13:42,943
[Alithea speaking]

216
01:13:44,479 --> 01:13:47,182
[creature speaking]

217
01:13:52,654 --> 01:13:54,623
[static buzzing on laptop]

218
01:14:05,167 --> 01:14:07,369
[The Djinn speaking]

219
01:14:09,671 --> 01:14:11,873
[static buzzing]

220
01:14:11,907 --> 01:14:14,509
[Einstein speaking
indistinctly on TV]

221
01:14:28,924 --> 01:14:29,957
Einstein.

222
01:14:29,990 --> 01:14:31,326
[The Djinn] Einstein.

223
01:14:38,800 --> 01:14:39,967
[in English]

224
01:14:40,001 --> 01:14:41,470
[The Djinn] Television.

225
01:14:41,503 --> 01:14:43,305
[in ancient Greek]

226
01:14:46,641 --> 01:14:48,143
[in English]

227
01:14:48,176 --> 01:14:49,811
[The Djinn] Transmitters.

228
01:14:49,845 --> 01:14:52,581
[in ancient Greek]

229
01:14:59,387 --> 01:15:01,256
[in English] I am a
djinn of modest power,

230
01:15:01,289 --> 01:15:05,894
but I begin to understand
these transmissions.

231
01:15:05,927 --> 01:15:07,229
Oh!

232
01:15:07,262 --> 01:15:09,764
You've learned
to speak my language.

233
01:15:09,798 --> 01:15:12,767
This English is straightforward.

234
01:15:12,801 --> 01:15:15,103
Its rules quickly learn, I find.

235
01:15:15,136 --> 01:15:16,505
[static buzzes]

236
01:15:16,538 --> 01:15:18,273
[Einstein gasping]

237
01:15:18,707 --> 01:15:20,141
[gasps]

238
01:15:20,175 --> 01:15:21,409
[Einstein] <i>Nein, nein, nein.</i>

239
01:15:21,443 --> 01:15:22,954
Would you like this
little Albert for yourself?

240
01:15:22,978 --> 01:15:24,279
No, no, no.

241
01:15:24,312 --> 01:15:25,857
That can't be good for him.
Put him back.

242
01:15:25,881 --> 01:15:27,124
- I could expand him.
- [Einstein] How?

243
01:15:27,148 --> 01:15:28,250
We could speak with him.

244
01:15:28,283 --> 01:15:29,660
- How is this possible?
- No, put him back.

245
01:15:29,684 --> 01:15:31,786
- Is that your wish?
- This is not possible.

246
01:15:31,820 --> 01:15:33,655
No. It's your obligation.

247
01:15:35,423 --> 01:15:36,258
[blows]

248
01:15:36,291 --> 01:15:37,726
[Einstein resumes speech
in German]

249
01:15:38,894 --> 01:15:41,463
So, what will you wish for?

250
01:15:41,496 --> 01:15:42,864
[floor creaks]

251
01:15:42,898 --> 01:15:45,100
What is your heart's desire?

252
01:15:50,171 --> 01:15:54,976
Now, let's, uh,
not get ahead of ourselves.

253
01:15:55,011 --> 01:15:57,979
I need to take this slow.
[sighs]

254
01:15:58,014 --> 01:16:01,316
I have all the time
in the world.

255
01:16:01,349 --> 01:16:03,618
Tell me about yourself.

256
01:16:03,652 --> 01:16:05,420
My name is Alithea Binnie.

257
01:16:05,453 --> 01:16:07,923
I am in Turkey for a conference.

258
01:16:07,956 --> 01:16:10,559
And I return to my homeland
in a day's time.

259
01:16:10,592 --> 01:16:11,760
Also?

260
01:16:11,793 --> 01:16:14,296
[Alithea breathing heavily]

261
01:16:14,329 --> 01:16:18,199
Also, I have
a confession to make.

262
01:16:18,233 --> 01:16:20,268
Something
I've never told anybody.

263
01:16:20,302 --> 01:16:21,703
[The Djinn] Excellent.

264
01:16:22,938 --> 01:16:25,874
When I was young,
there was a boy.

265
01:16:25,907 --> 01:16:27,208
Your first lover?

266
01:16:27,242 --> 01:16:30,345
No, no, no.
He was not of flesh and blood.

267
01:16:30,378 --> 01:16:31,613
A djinn?

268
01:16:31,646 --> 01:16:33,515
No.

269
01:16:33,548 --> 01:16:37,586
At that time, I found myself
in a school for girls.

270
01:16:37,619 --> 01:16:39,321
<i>Gaggles of girls.</i>

271
01:16:39,354 --> 01:16:44,159
<i>I was... Well, I am
a solitary creature by nature.</i>

272
01:16:44,192 --> 01:16:47,195
<i>And this boy, Enzo,</i>

273
01:16:47,228 --> 01:16:50,298
<i>he came to me,
out of an emptiness.</i>

274
01:16:51,399 --> 01:16:54,336
<i>Out of a need to imagine.</i>

275
01:16:54,369 --> 01:16:56,271
He told me stories in a language

276
01:16:56,304 --> 01:16:58,673
that only we two spoke.

277
01:17:00,076 --> 01:17:02,210
And he always disappeared
when I had a headache,

278
01:17:02,243 --> 01:17:03,478
but he was never far away

279
01:17:03,511 --> 01:17:05,747
when I couldn't move for asthma.

280
01:17:05,780 --> 01:17:07,849
[The Djinn] <i>He was like</i>
<i>this little Albert</i>

281
01:17:07,882 --> 01:17:09,484
<i>you would not let me give you?</i>

282
01:17:09,517 --> 01:17:11,186
<i>An emanation?</i>

283
01:17:11,219 --> 01:17:14,122
[Alithea] <i>Only an emanation</i>
<i>of an absence.</i>

284
01:17:14,155 --> 01:17:16,925
[breathing laboriously]

285
01:17:16,958 --> 01:17:20,562
<i>I feared he would leave,
and so I wrote him down.</i>

286
01:17:22,464 --> 01:17:27,235
<i>And I filled this journal,
bulging with facts.</i>

287
01:17:28,503 --> 01:17:32,841
But the more realism
I tried to insert,

288
01:17:32,874 --> 01:17:35,644
the more I began to doubt,

289
01:17:35,677 --> 01:17:38,880
and, uh, it all began
to feel silly.

290
01:17:40,116 --> 01:17:41,783
I felt silly.

291
01:17:43,685 --> 01:17:46,122
So, after a time,

292
01:17:46,154 --> 01:17:48,623
I burned it all
in the school furnace.

293
01:17:50,692 --> 01:17:53,628
And after that,
he disappeared altogether.

294
01:17:54,963 --> 01:17:57,499
And yet, I am here.

295
01:17:59,801 --> 01:18:01,770
Contrary to reason, yes.

296
01:18:02,937 --> 01:18:07,009
I am here,
and we have work to do.

297
01:18:07,043 --> 01:18:08,343
[knocking at door]

298
01:18:09,310 --> 01:18:11,646
Can you come back later, please?

299
01:18:11,680 --> 01:18:13,815
[man] It's room service,
Dr. Binnie.

300
01:18:13,848 --> 01:18:15,850
I have your breakfast.

301
01:18:15,884 --> 01:18:17,419
[Alithea] Just a minute!

302
01:18:18,620 --> 01:18:20,221
Must close door.

303
01:18:34,302 --> 01:18:35,403
Good morning.

304
01:18:35,437 --> 01:18:36,814
Where would you like it,
Dr. Binnie?

305
01:18:36,838 --> 01:18:37,772
Thank you. Oh, I can take it.

306
01:18:37,806 --> 01:18:40,009
- Please, allow me.
- No. No, I can manage it.

307
01:18:40,042 --> 01:18:42,977
Jolly good, Dr. Binnie.
I hope you are well rested.

308
01:18:43,012 --> 01:18:44,546
Oh, that looks delicious.
Yes, I am.

309
01:18:44,579 --> 01:18:46,357
[man] What do you plan to do
on this fine day?

310
01:18:46,381 --> 01:18:48,883
Uh, I'm not sure.
I'm improvising.

311
01:18:48,917 --> 01:18:51,786
Well, I'd like to show you
a beautiful art gallery...

312
01:18:51,820 --> 01:18:52,721
That's so kind. Thank you.

313
01:18:52,754 --> 01:18:54,032
...this afternoon,
when you get a chance.

314
01:18:54,056 --> 01:18:55,332
- Maybe another time.
- It will be great.

315
01:18:55,356 --> 01:18:56,400
Thank you.
Have a beautiful day.

316
01:18:56,424 --> 01:18:58,727
[man] Okay. Jolly good. Enjoy.

317
01:18:58,760 --> 01:18:59,928
Thank you!

318
01:19:04,966 --> 01:19:07,435
[people chattering in distance]

319
01:19:16,778 --> 01:19:18,313
[lock clicks]

320
01:19:39,201 --> 01:19:41,936
A more convenient size, I see.

321
01:19:41,970 --> 01:19:43,838
I do what I can to fit in.

322
01:19:44,206 --> 01:19:46,108
Please.

323
01:19:46,142 --> 01:19:48,309
I needn't have
ordered breakfast.

324
01:19:48,343 --> 01:19:51,946
It's nan-e nokhodchi.
Chickpeas, cloves, pistachio.

325
01:19:51,980 --> 01:19:53,715
It will melt in your mouth.

326
01:19:58,920 --> 01:20:00,889
May I ask you something?

327
01:20:00,922 --> 01:20:01,990
[The Djinn] Anything.

328
01:20:03,324 --> 01:20:06,262
How come you found your way
into my bottle?

329
01:20:07,395 --> 01:20:08,897
Ah, it's quite a story.

330
01:20:09,697 --> 01:20:11,733
That was my third incarceration.

331
01:20:11,766 --> 01:20:13,835
You've been trapped
in a bottle three times?

332
01:20:13,868 --> 01:20:16,005
I may be a djinn,
but I'm also a fool

333
01:20:16,038 --> 01:20:18,807
with too great a fondness
for the conversation of women.

334
01:20:18,840 --> 01:20:21,177
I need to be more careful
in the future.

335
01:20:21,210 --> 01:20:22,744
How were you caught
in the first place?

336
01:20:23,678 --> 01:20:25,147
By desire.

337
01:20:25,181 --> 01:20:26,948
How else?

338
01:20:29,918 --> 01:20:31,519
Who was she?

339
01:20:31,553 --> 01:20:32,954
Sheba.

340
01:20:32,987 --> 01:20:34,156
The Queen of Sheba?

341
01:20:34,190 --> 01:20:35,890
She was my kin.

342
01:20:35,924 --> 01:20:37,026
She was a djinn?

343
01:20:37,059 --> 01:20:38,359
Her mother was a djinn.

344
01:20:38,393 --> 01:20:39,460
Is that possible?

345
01:20:39,494 --> 01:20:40,628
There are laws that allow

346
01:20:40,662 --> 01:20:42,164
the union of djinn and mortals,

347
01:20:42,198 --> 01:20:44,099
but they cannot produce
an immortal scion

348
01:20:44,133 --> 01:20:45,243
the way a donkey and a horse

349
01:20:45,267 --> 01:20:47,368
can only produce
a seedless mule.

350
01:20:49,038 --> 01:20:51,940
So, what did she look like?

351
01:20:51,973 --> 01:20:56,178
Other than a thick glade
of black hair on her legs,

352
01:20:56,212 --> 01:20:57,588
she looked like
any other human being,

353
01:20:57,612 --> 01:20:59,881
except, of course,
she was Sheba.

354
01:20:59,914 --> 01:21:02,517
By all accounts,
she was very beautiful.

355
01:21:02,550 --> 01:21:05,620
She was not beautiful.
She was beauty itself.

356
01:21:09,191 --> 01:21:11,793
I was in every way free.

357
01:21:11,826 --> 01:21:14,963
I would come in and out
of her sleeping chamber.

358
01:21:16,165 --> 01:21:18,633
[whispers] Sheba...

359
01:21:20,236 --> 01:21:21,936
[blows]

360
01:21:21,970 --> 01:21:24,873
<i>I knew as well as any
of her female slaves</i>

361
01:21:24,906 --> 01:21:28,010
<i>the touches that made
her shiver with bliss.</i>

362
01:21:29,211 --> 01:21:31,679
<i>Never have I wanted
a creature so.</i>

363
01:21:32,380 --> 01:21:33,815
And she desired you in return?

364
01:21:33,848 --> 01:21:37,219
I was her plaything.
Her confidante.

365
01:21:37,253 --> 01:21:39,487
I might have become more,
but for Solomon.

366
01:21:39,520 --> 01:21:40,889
King Solomon?

367
01:21:40,922 --> 01:21:42,690
Blessed be his memory.

368
01:21:42,724 --> 01:21:45,160
He came from across
the deserts to woo her.

369
01:21:45,194 --> 01:21:46,295
Didn't she go to him?

370
01:21:46,328 --> 01:21:47,629
No. Never.

371
01:21:47,662 --> 01:21:49,464
But it's in all the holy books.

372
01:21:49,497 --> 01:21:51,133
All the stories
and the paintings.

373
01:21:51,166 --> 01:21:52,934
And Handel wrote music about it.

374
01:21:52,967 --> 01:21:54,336
Madam, I was there.

375
01:21:54,370 --> 01:21:56,205
Solomon came to her.

376
01:21:56,238 --> 01:21:58,773
[people chattering in distance]

377
01:21:58,806 --> 01:22:01,809
[The Djinn speaking
early Aramaic]

378
01:22:20,828 --> 01:22:23,431
[strums note]

379
01:22:23,464 --> 01:22:25,533
[The Djinn in English]
<i>he began with music.</i>

380
01:22:26,402 --> 01:22:28,636
[playing romantic melody]

381
01:22:30,306 --> 01:22:32,107
[music intensifying]

382
01:22:32,141 --> 01:22:33,541
[music stops abruptly]

383
01:22:44,420 --> 01:22:47,622
[playing sentimental music]

384
01:23:17,518 --> 01:23:20,155
[sentimental music continues]

385
01:23:46,415 --> 01:23:48,250
[music ends in flourish]

386
01:23:54,289 --> 01:23:55,290
[gulps]

387
01:23:57,026 --> 01:24:00,429
I did all that I could
to dissuade her.

388
01:24:00,462 --> 01:24:01,562
But when she used

389
01:24:01,596 --> 01:24:03,432
the scented wax
of the Jabassa Bee

390
01:24:03,465 --> 01:24:05,167
to remove the hair
from her legs,

391
01:24:05,200 --> 01:24:06,701
<i>I knew that I was lost.</i>

392
01:24:06,734 --> 01:24:09,038
<i>But I, like a fool,
went on telling her</i>

393
01:24:09,071 --> 01:24:12,007
<i>that her body
was rich and lovely,</i>

394
01:24:12,041 --> 01:24:14,709
<i>but her mind
was richer and lovelier,</i>

395
01:24:14,742 --> 01:24:16,478
<i>and more durable.</i>

396
01:24:16,512 --> 01:24:18,579
<i>And she agreed
with all that I said,</i>

397
01:24:18,613 --> 01:24:20,315
<i>and dropped a hot tear.</i>

398
01:24:21,616 --> 01:24:24,585
She began to set him tasks,
which seemed impossible,

399
01:24:24,619 --> 01:24:26,687
to find a particular thread
of red silk

400
01:24:26,721 --> 01:24:28,689
in the palace
of a thousand rooms,

401
01:24:28,723 --> 01:24:31,592
to guess the secret name
of her mother djinn,

402
01:24:31,626 --> 01:24:34,862
[inhales] to tell her
what women most desire.

403
01:24:34,896 --> 01:24:36,964
That does seem impossible.

404
01:24:36,998 --> 01:24:37,932
Not for him.

405
01:24:37,965 --> 01:24:39,576
He could speak
to the beasts of the earth,

406
01:24:39,600 --> 01:24:41,969
and to the djinn
made of subtle fire.

407
01:24:42,004 --> 01:24:45,040
<i>He found ants to discover
the thread of silk,</i>

408
01:24:45,074 --> 01:24:47,342
<i>and an ifrit to whisper
the mother's name.</i>

409
01:24:47,376 --> 01:24:49,777
[ifrit speaking indistinctly]

410
01:24:52,281 --> 01:24:53,981
[The Djinn] <i>Then he looked</i>
<i>into her eyes</i>

411
01:24:54,016 --> 01:24:57,052
<i>and told her
what women most desire.</i>

412
01:24:57,086 --> 01:24:59,354
[King Solomon speaking
early Aramaic]

413
01:24:59,388 --> 01:25:00,922
[The Djinn] <i>She was astonished,</i>

414
01:25:02,357 --> 01:25:04,093
<i>and told him he was right.</i>

415
01:25:08,297 --> 01:25:11,999
<i>And so she granted him
what he most desired,</i>

416
01:25:12,034 --> 01:25:15,037
<i>which was to wed her
and be taken to her bed.</i>

417
01:25:19,074 --> 01:25:20,242
[Sheba gasps]

418
01:25:20,275 --> 01:25:22,777
[distorted screaming]

419
01:25:24,979 --> 01:25:27,782
[emotional string music playing]

420
01:25:28,484 --> 01:25:30,718
[whooshing softly]

421
01:25:33,522 --> 01:25:34,989
[speaks early Aramaic]

422
01:25:35,023 --> 01:25:36,757
[The Djinn]
<i>He was a great magician...</i>

423
01:25:36,791 --> 01:25:38,227
- [wheezing]
<i>- ...and imprisoned me</i>

424
01:25:38,260 --> 01:25:41,662
<i>with a word of power
into a brass bottle.</i>

425
01:25:45,601 --> 01:25:48,703
[emotional string
music continues]

426
01:26:07,655 --> 01:26:09,924
<i>She made no plea for me.</i>

427
01:26:10,791 --> 01:26:13,328
<i>I was nothing to her.</i>

428
01:26:13,362 --> 01:26:15,230
<i>A breath in a bottle.</i>

429
01:26:29,844 --> 01:26:32,614
<i>And so, I was cast
into the Red Sea</i>

430
01:26:32,648 --> 01:26:36,351
<i>and languished for 2,500 years.</i>

431
01:26:41,590 --> 01:26:43,158
Apart from sleep,

432
01:26:43,192 --> 01:26:46,295
what does one do in a bottle
for 2,500 years?

433
01:26:47,695 --> 01:26:49,331
Djinn don't sleep.

434
01:26:54,869 --> 01:26:56,737
So, how do you manage then?

435
01:26:57,439 --> 01:26:58,440
[clicks tongue]

436
01:26:59,907 --> 01:27:04,613
Well, for the first 100 years,
I rage against my fate.

437
01:27:04,646 --> 01:27:06,515
I pray to Boschkolo
for my release,

438
01:27:06,548 --> 01:27:07,782
and when that does not work,

439
01:27:07,815 --> 01:27:09,251
I pray to any god I know,

440
01:27:09,284 --> 01:27:11,420
and then to any god
I may not know.

441
01:27:11,453 --> 01:27:14,122
And when, still,
I find no answers,

442
01:27:14,156 --> 01:27:14,989
[inhales]

443
01:27:15,023 --> 01:27:17,092
I spend my time in waking dreams

444
01:27:17,125 --> 01:27:19,927
revisiting all the stories
of my life.

445
01:27:19,961 --> 01:27:22,830
And when I have exhausted this
many, many times,

446
01:27:22,863 --> 01:27:25,866
I return to my prayer
and my rage.

447
01:27:25,900 --> 01:27:29,004
And then, finally,

448
01:27:30,405 --> 01:27:32,474
I play a trick on myself.

449
01:27:33,808 --> 01:27:35,244
I pray to remain in the bottle.

450
01:27:35,277 --> 01:27:39,248
I beseech Boschkolo to keep me
always in the bottle.

451
01:27:39,281 --> 01:27:40,649
And does that work?

452
01:27:40,682 --> 01:27:42,117
To yearn for nothing?

453
01:27:42,150 --> 01:27:43,985
To pretend to want nothing more

454
01:27:44,019 --> 01:27:45,953
than to be contained
in a bottle?

455
01:27:45,987 --> 01:27:47,189
No.

456
01:27:47,222 --> 01:27:50,092
For a djinn, it is the closest
we ever come to death.

457
01:27:51,360 --> 01:27:52,827
[sighs]

458
01:27:52,860 --> 01:27:54,596
Do you know the answer
to her question?

459
01:27:54,630 --> 01:27:55,997
What women most desire?

460
01:27:56,031 --> 01:27:57,099
Yeah.

461
01:27:57,132 --> 01:27:58,634
Do you not know?

462
01:27:58,667 --> 01:28:00,168
If you do not know,
I cannot tell you.

463
01:28:00,202 --> 01:28:02,337
Well, surely, we don't
all want the same thing.

464
01:28:02,371 --> 01:28:05,973
Madam, your yearnings
are not at all clear to me.

465
01:28:06,008 --> 01:28:09,278
I... I'm at a point in my life
where I have all I need.

466
01:28:09,311 --> 01:28:12,047
I daresay I'm content,
and gratefully so.

467
01:28:12,080 --> 01:28:12,980
Tell me.

468
01:28:13,015 --> 01:28:15,550
Are you a wife? A widow?

469
01:28:15,584 --> 01:28:17,419
- Um...
- A mother, perhaps?

470
01:28:17,452 --> 01:28:20,289
I have no children,
no siblings, no parents.

471
01:28:21,989 --> 01:28:23,425
I did once have a husband.

472
01:28:23,458 --> 01:28:24,393
[The Djinn] Ah.

473
01:28:24,426 --> 01:28:26,827
And what was the complexion
of this husband?

474
01:28:27,396 --> 01:28:28,630
His complexion?

475
01:28:28,664 --> 01:28:31,832
In the beginning,
it was glowing.

476
01:28:31,866 --> 01:28:33,635
And in the ending?

477
01:28:33,669 --> 01:28:35,170
It's not much of a story.

478
01:28:35,203 --> 01:28:38,273
But it is a story.
It is your story,

479
01:28:38,307 --> 01:28:39,741
and it is always wise

480
01:28:39,775 --> 01:28:41,677
to understand those
who have a hold on you.

481
01:28:41,710 --> 01:28:42,778
Please.

482
01:28:42,810 --> 01:28:44,046
[inhales deeply]

483
01:28:45,013 --> 01:28:47,316
[grunts] Well, okay, um...

484
01:28:48,483 --> 01:28:49,651
[smacks lips]

485
01:28:49,685 --> 01:28:52,354
We'd known each other
since our youth.

486
01:28:52,387 --> 01:28:54,022
<i>We, uh, married early.</i>

487
01:28:54,056 --> 01:28:55,956
<i>In the beginning,
we took pleasure</i>

488
01:28:55,990 --> 01:28:57,825
<i>in each other's minds
and bodies.</i>

489
01:28:57,858 --> 01:28:59,127
<i>Um...</i>

490
01:28:59,161 --> 01:29:00,961
<i>We passed the years comfortably,</i>

491
01:29:00,995 --> 01:29:03,532
<i>and then as it happens,</i>

492
01:29:04,333 --> 01:29:06,134
<i>it all evaporated,</i>

493
01:29:06,168 --> 01:29:08,337
<i>and, uh... and we became</i>

494
01:29:09,538 --> 01:29:10,572
less.

495
01:29:10,605 --> 01:29:11,606
And where is he?

496
01:29:13,108 --> 01:29:16,244
He's in Hackney,
with Emmeline Porter.

497
01:29:16,278 --> 01:29:17,379
[The Djinn] Mmm.

498
01:29:20,248 --> 01:29:21,416
[Alithea sighs]

499
01:29:23,618 --> 01:29:25,320
[Alithea] <i>He told me I...</i>

500
01:29:25,354 --> 01:29:27,823
<i>I was incapable
of reading feelings.</i>

501
01:29:27,855 --> 01:29:29,224
[car brakes]

502
01:29:29,257 --> 01:29:30,525
[car horn beeps]

503
01:29:31,992 --> 01:29:34,329
<i>I was incapable
of reading his feelings.</i>

504
01:29:34,363 --> 01:29:36,431
[Emmeline] ...gonna have
a resolution.

505
01:29:36,465 --> 01:29:37,366
[Jack] This is exciting!

506
01:29:37,399 --> 01:29:38,975
- It is exciting!
- [Emmeline] No, it's not.

507
01:29:38,999 --> 01:29:40,602
Let me guess.
No one dies in it.

508
01:29:40,635 --> 01:29:42,137
[Emmeline laughing] No!

509
01:29:42,170 --> 01:29:45,973
[Alithea] <i>The way my brain</i>
<i>is wired is... is the...</i>

510
01:29:46,007 --> 01:29:48,976
the source both of my power

511
01:29:49,010 --> 01:29:51,912
and, uh, and my solitude.

512
01:29:52,748 --> 01:29:55,050
I suspect that's why
I like stories.

513
01:29:55,851 --> 01:29:58,653
I find feelings through stories.

514
01:29:58,687 --> 01:30:00,988
[The Djinn sighs]

515
01:30:02,090 --> 01:30:04,992
Perhaps you could
wish for him back.

516
01:30:05,026 --> 01:30:07,295
Oh, no, no, no. No, no, no.

517
01:30:07,529 --> 01:30:08,530
No.

518
01:30:09,698 --> 01:30:12,300
I... I thought, um,

519
01:30:13,268 --> 01:30:17,205
I might grieve
a loss and betrayal, but, uh,

520
01:30:18,573 --> 01:30:20,208
no, in fact, I was free.

521
01:30:21,676 --> 01:30:23,812
I was like a prisoner

522
01:30:23,845 --> 01:30:27,416
emerging from a dungeon
into the sunlight.

523
01:30:27,449 --> 01:30:30,252
I expanded into the space
of my own life.

524
01:30:30,285 --> 01:30:34,389
No, I could not wish for more.

525
01:30:34,423 --> 01:30:37,626
You are a wise
and cautious woman, Alithea.

526
01:30:37,659 --> 01:30:40,095
But we all have desires,

527
01:30:40,128 --> 01:30:42,130
even if they remain
hidden from us.

528
01:30:42,631 --> 01:30:44,266
[inhales sharply]

529
01:30:44,299 --> 01:30:45,901
That's as maybe.

530
01:30:45,933 --> 01:30:50,839
But I am also a narratologist,

531
01:30:50,872 --> 01:30:53,308
and that is going
to be a problem.

532
01:30:53,341 --> 01:30:55,744
It's going to be
a very big problem.

533
01:30:55,777 --> 01:30:57,779
See, I know
all the stories there are

534
01:30:57,813 --> 01:30:59,014
about trickster djinn,

535
01:30:59,047 --> 01:31:00,658
and the ways in which
they manipulate wishing

536
01:31:00,682 --> 01:31:01,716
to their own ends.

537
01:31:01,750 --> 01:31:02,851
I am not one of them.

538
01:31:02,884 --> 01:31:04,586
I am god-fearing and honorable,

539
01:31:04,619 --> 01:31:07,055
and only here
to grant your heart's desire.

540
01:31:07,088 --> 01:31:09,157
Well, even if that's true,

541
01:31:09,191 --> 01:31:12,461
how can you rely on those
called upon to wish?

542
01:31:13,161 --> 01:31:14,396
[speaks ancient Greek]

543
01:31:14,429 --> 01:31:17,299
How do you know
you can rely on me?

544
01:31:18,533 --> 01:31:20,335
Well, I hope so.

545
01:31:20,368 --> 01:31:23,371
With you, I certainly hope so.

546
01:31:23,405 --> 01:31:25,373
There's a...

547
01:31:25,407 --> 01:31:28,310
funny little story.
I mean, you probably know it.

548
01:31:28,343 --> 01:31:30,245
Three friends lost at sea
in a tiny boat.

549
01:31:30,278 --> 01:31:32,013
They pull up a magic fish,

550
01:31:32,047 --> 01:31:33,748
who grants each of them
one wish.

551
01:31:33,782 --> 01:31:34,816
The first one,

552
01:31:34,850 --> 01:31:36,651
"I wish I were at home
with my wife."

553
01:31:36,685 --> 01:31:37,552
He vanishes.

554
01:31:37,586 --> 01:31:39,254
The second one,
"I wish I were playing"

555
01:31:39,287 --> 01:31:40,755
"in the fields
with my children."

556
01:31:40,789 --> 01:31:41,890
Off he goes.

557
01:31:41,923 --> 01:31:44,493
And the third one,
"I miss my friends..."

558
01:31:44,526 --> 01:31:45,560
"I wish they were here."

559
01:31:45,594 --> 01:31:46,828
You've got it.

560
01:31:46,862 --> 01:31:50,465
There's no story about wishing
that is not a cautionary tale.

561
01:31:50,499 --> 01:31:52,200
None end happily.

562
01:31:52,234 --> 01:31:54,111
Not even the ones
that are supposed to be jokes.

563
01:31:54,135 --> 01:31:56,605
But you and I
are the authors of this story,

564
01:31:56,638 --> 01:31:59,107
and we can avoid all traps.

565
01:32:00,842 --> 01:32:03,211
Well, what if
I made no wish at all?

566
01:32:05,013 --> 01:32:06,214
Pardon?

567
01:32:08,850 --> 01:32:10,752
What if I made no wish?

568
01:32:10,785 --> 01:32:11,953
That would be an...

569
01:32:11,987 --> 01:32:14,456
- [electricity humming]
- [soft squelching]

570
01:32:14,489 --> 01:32:15,690
That would be

571
01:32:15,724 --> 01:32:17,959
catastrophic! [Echoes]

572
01:32:17,993 --> 01:32:20,295
[flesh crunching]

573
01:32:21,830 --> 01:32:23,465
[panting]

574
01:32:26,535 --> 01:32:29,037
[The Djinn muttering
incoherently]

575
01:32:29,070 --> 01:32:31,373
[The Djinn breathing heavily]

576
01:32:32,008 --> 01:32:33,542
[Alithea] All right.

577
01:32:33,575 --> 01:32:36,645
- [panting heavily]
- [crunching subsides]

578
01:32:38,213 --> 01:32:41,416
I need to tell you
about my next incarceration.

579
01:32:41,449 --> 01:32:42,450
I'm all ears.

580
01:32:42,751 --> 01:32:44,252
[sighs]

581
01:32:53,428 --> 01:32:55,130
[The Djinn] <i>I will never know</i>

582
01:32:55,163 --> 01:32:59,035
<i>how my bottle came from the
bottom of the Red Sea...</i>

583
01:32:59,067 --> 01:33:00,101
[flies buzzing]

584
01:33:00,135 --> 01:33:02,604
<i>...to a palace
in Constantinople.</i>

585
01:33:03,605 --> 01:33:05,507
<i>But I fancy somehow it involved</i>

586
01:33:05,540 --> 01:33:07,142
<i>the killing of
an Ottoman warrior.</i>

587
01:33:07,175 --> 01:33:09,210
[takes deep breath]

588
01:33:13,148 --> 01:33:14,783
<i>The fall of an empire.</i>

589
01:33:17,786 --> 01:33:19,854
[wall crumbling]

590
01:33:24,092 --> 01:33:25,293
<i>And a girl in love.</i>

591
01:33:25,327 --> 01:33:29,230
[girl muttering
in Ottoman Turkish]

592
01:33:35,370 --> 01:33:38,506
[girl singing
in Ottoman Turkish]

593
01:33:47,016 --> 01:33:48,483
[girl] <i>Merhaba.</i>

594
01:33:49,150 --> 01:33:50,352
[gasps]

595
01:33:51,686 --> 01:33:52,754
[bottle clangs]

596
01:33:52,787 --> 01:33:55,256
[high-pitched pinging]

597
01:33:58,760 --> 01:34:00,662
[in Ottoman Turkish]

598
01:34:00,695 --> 01:34:03,498
[eerie music playing]

599
01:34:05,001 --> 01:34:08,336
[hammering]

600
01:34:08,370 --> 01:34:10,072
[girl muttering
in Ottoman Turkish]

601
01:34:10,106 --> 01:34:12,574
[The Djinn in English]
<i>Gulten lived as a slave</i>

602
01:34:12,607 --> 01:34:14,643
<i>in the courtyard
of the concubines</i>

603
01:34:14,676 --> 01:34:15,777
<i>in the seraglio.</i>

604
01:34:15,810 --> 01:34:18,179
[Gulten continues muttering
in Ottoman Turkish]

605
01:34:18,213 --> 01:34:20,215
[rumbling]

606
01:34:20,248 --> 01:34:21,883
[Gulten gasping]

607
01:34:24,552 --> 01:34:26,254
[shuddering]

608
01:34:28,189 --> 01:34:30,225
[The Djinn breathing heavily]

609
01:34:33,062 --> 01:34:35,163
- [The Djinn growls softly]
- [Gulten gasps]

610
01:34:35,196 --> 01:34:36,540
[The Djinn]
<i>When I appeared to her...</i>

611
01:34:36,564 --> 01:34:38,233
[gasps]

612
01:34:39,167 --> 01:34:41,302
<i>...she fainted.</i>

613
01:34:41,336 --> 01:34:44,040
<i>And I had great trouble
rousing her.</i>

614
01:34:44,073 --> 01:34:47,342
[The Djinn whispering
in Ottoman Turkish]

615
01:34:50,211 --> 01:34:52,681
I made it clear
that I meant her no harm,

616
01:34:52,714 --> 01:34:54,516
for I was condemned
to the bottle.

617
01:34:54,549 --> 01:34:56,085
Until you got your three wishes.

618
01:34:56,118 --> 01:34:58,054
- Until she got hers.
- [Alithea scoffs]

619
01:34:58,087 --> 01:35:00,221
- Please.
- Okay.

620
01:35:00,255 --> 01:35:01,690
Now, the poor girl told me

621
01:35:01,723 --> 01:35:05,827
she was distractedly in love
with a beautiful man...

622
01:35:05,860 --> 01:35:07,129
[speaking Ottoman Turkish]

623
01:35:07,163 --> 01:35:08,797
[The Djinn]
<i>...and she wished immediately</i>

624
01:35:08,830 --> 01:35:11,033
<i>to find favor in his eyes.</i>

625
01:35:11,067 --> 01:35:13,368
[man speaking Ottoman Turkish]

626
01:35:22,911 --> 01:35:24,013
[blows]

627
01:35:24,046 --> 01:35:25,389
[The Djinn in English]
<i>As it happens,</i>

628
01:35:25,413 --> 01:35:27,982
<i>the one she most desired
was the splendid Mustafa.</i>

629
01:35:28,017 --> 01:35:29,751
<i>Prince Mustafa.</i>

630
01:35:31,586 --> 01:35:34,255
<i>Eldest son of
Suleiman the Magnificent,</i>

631
01:35:34,289 --> 01:35:37,459
<i>and likely heir
to his mighty throne.</i>

632
01:35:38,426 --> 01:35:39,994
<i>Had I known what was to come,</i>

633
01:35:40,029 --> 01:35:43,132
I would've risked
the furies of Iblis

634
01:35:43,165 --> 01:35:46,434
to vehemently distract her
from her wish.

635
01:35:47,902 --> 01:35:49,337
<i>But without thinking,</i>

636
01:35:49,370 --> 01:35:52,108
<i>I took my bottle
and conjured oils</i>

637
01:35:52,141 --> 01:35:53,708
<i>to prepare her.</i>

638
01:35:55,343 --> 01:35:57,046
<i>Oils of enchantment</i>

639
01:35:57,079 --> 01:36:00,248
<i>once used only by Sheba.</i>

640
01:36:04,719 --> 01:36:06,821
<i>I cautioned her
to hide the bottle</i>

641
01:36:06,855 --> 01:36:09,858
<i>lest its powers
fall into other hands.</i>

642
01:36:15,164 --> 01:36:16,765
<i>I went to Mustafa.</i>

643
01:36:16,798 --> 01:36:18,500
[whispers] Gulten.

644
01:36:18,533 --> 01:36:19,968
<i>I whispered her name.</i>

645
01:36:24,706 --> 01:36:26,374
<i>He sent for her.</i>

646
01:36:28,843 --> 01:36:30,578
<i>It was so easy.</i>

647
01:36:37,652 --> 01:36:39,188
[traditional music playing]

648
01:36:39,221 --> 01:36:41,389
<i>As a djinn,
I am endlessly curious</i>

649
01:36:41,422 --> 01:36:43,358
<i>about the ways of humans.</i>

650
01:36:44,226 --> 01:36:45,627
<i>So, in my spare time,</i>

651
01:36:45,660 --> 01:36:49,531
<i>I took to wandering the palace
in search of its intrigues.</i>

652
01:36:50,298 --> 01:36:51,766
<i>And there, among the eunuchs,</i>

653
01:36:51,800 --> 01:36:53,535
<i>the consorts,
and the concubines,</i>

654
01:36:53,568 --> 01:36:55,804
<i>I first saw Hurrem.</i>

655
01:36:56,838 --> 01:36:58,174
<i>The Laughing One.</i>

656
01:36:58,207 --> 01:36:59,275
[Hurrem laughing]

657
01:36:59,307 --> 01:37:01,876
[Hurrem speaking
Ottoman Turkish]

658
01:37:02,811 --> 01:37:04,445
[people clamoring]

659
01:37:06,748 --> 01:37:08,716
[The Djinn]
<i>She, too, was a slave</i>

660
01:37:08,750 --> 01:37:11,452
<i>who had risen
through the center of them all</i>

661
01:37:11,486 --> 01:37:13,888
<i>to become the Sultan's favorite.</i>

662
01:37:16,292 --> 01:37:18,493
[crowd gasping in awe]

663
01:37:22,397 --> 01:37:26,135
<i>Suleiman the Wise
saw none but her.</i>

664
01:37:26,168 --> 01:37:28,670
<i>And she sought
to protect his throne</i>

665
01:37:28,703 --> 01:37:32,941
<i>in favor of her own sons
over his beloved Mustafa.</i>

666
01:37:35,710 --> 01:37:38,080
<i>And to this end,
she had the prince watched</i>

667
01:37:38,113 --> 01:37:39,814
<i>by many probing eyes.</i>

668
01:37:44,686 --> 01:37:46,688
[laughing]

669
01:37:49,991 --> 01:37:51,359
<i>When I saw how Hurrem</i>

670
01:37:51,392 --> 01:37:55,197
<i>made a masterpiece
of her manipulations,</i>

671
01:37:55,231 --> 01:37:59,367
<i>I worried that my Gulten
might be caught in this web.</i>

672
01:38:05,241 --> 01:38:07,375
<i>I tried to warn her
to be careful.</i>

673
01:38:07,408 --> 01:38:09,078
[both speaking Ottoman Turkish]

674
01:38:09,111 --> 01:38:12,847
<i>But she had already
decided on her second wish.</i>

675
01:38:12,881 --> 01:38:14,716
[in Ottoman Turkish]

676
01:38:25,460 --> 01:38:27,662
[in English] <i>Such a mistake.</i>

677
01:38:28,563 --> 01:38:30,632
<i>Because at this moment,</i>

678
01:38:30,665 --> 01:38:33,068
<i>Suleiman, blessed be his name,</i>

679
01:38:33,102 --> 01:38:34,802
<i>is being undermined.</i>

680
01:38:35,870 --> 01:38:38,539
<i>His warriors believe
he is going soft,</i>

681
01:38:38,573 --> 01:38:41,277
<i>more interested in his poetry</i>

682
01:38:41,310 --> 01:38:43,912
<i>than ruling with a strong hand.</i>

683
01:38:43,945 --> 01:38:46,514
[arguing indistinctly]

684
01:38:51,120 --> 01:38:53,122
[speaking Ottoman Turkish]

685
01:38:59,261 --> 01:39:00,995
[The Djinn] <i>Hurrem</i>
<i>fuels the rumors</i>

686
01:39:01,030 --> 01:39:03,198
<i>that the military
want to take his throne</i>

687
01:39:03,232 --> 01:39:05,633
<i>and replace him with Mustafa.</i>

688
01:39:06,734 --> 01:39:08,370
<i>The prince has become a pawn</i>

689
01:39:08,404 --> 01:39:11,373
<i>in the ceaseless game of power.</i>

690
01:39:11,407 --> 01:39:13,741
[arguing continues indistinctly]

691
01:39:23,651 --> 01:39:25,687
<i>Suleiman the Magnificent,</i>

692
01:39:25,720 --> 01:39:27,423
<i>Suleiman the Conqueror,</i>

693
01:39:27,455 --> 01:39:30,292
<i>patron and protector of empires,</i>

694
01:39:30,326 --> 01:39:32,027
<i>Suleiman the Father,</i>

695
01:39:32,061 --> 01:39:33,362
<i>was left with a choice</i>

696
01:39:33,395 --> 01:39:36,564
<i>that he knows
will break his heart.</i>

697
01:39:43,471 --> 01:39:46,408
<i>Gulten, meantime, saw no reason</i>

698
01:39:46,442 --> 01:39:49,044
<i>why she should remain unseen.</i>

699
01:39:49,078 --> 01:39:50,878
[Gulten laughing loudly]

700
01:39:52,547 --> 01:39:56,684
<i>Given she was carrying the son
of the next Sultan.</i>

701
01:40:02,557 --> 01:40:04,625
<i>Despite all my warnings,</i>

702
01:40:04,659 --> 01:40:08,730
<i>she parades her newly swollen
breasts and belly.</i>

703
01:40:08,763 --> 01:40:12,368
<i>And the whispers soon spread
throughout the seraglio.</i>

704
01:40:12,401 --> 01:40:15,037
[tense music playing]

705
01:40:18,573 --> 01:40:22,011
<i>The terrible plottings
move all too quickly.</i>

706
01:40:27,216 --> 01:40:28,217
[tense music stops]

707
01:40:47,969 --> 01:40:50,439
<i>Prince Mustafa comes innocently</i>

708
01:40:50,472 --> 01:40:52,640
<i>into the presence of his father,</i>

709
01:40:52,673 --> 01:40:55,444
<i>to reassure him of his loyalty.</i>

710
01:40:55,477 --> 01:40:57,146
[Mustafa speaking
Ottoman Turkish]

711
01:41:04,520 --> 01:41:06,055
[grunting]

712
01:41:06,088 --> 01:41:08,723
[The Djinn in English] <i>And
the mutes are waiting for him.</i>

713
01:41:12,660 --> 01:41:14,595
<i>He cried out to his Janissaries,</i>

714
01:41:14,629 --> 01:41:15,930
<i>who loved him,</i>

715
01:41:15,963 --> 01:41:18,933
<i>but his voice was crushed
and his breath stopped</i>

716
01:41:18,966 --> 01:41:21,803
<i>by the string
of his father's bow.</i>

717
01:41:27,842 --> 01:41:31,046
[muffled humming of tune]

718
01:41:37,152 --> 01:41:39,587
[continues humming tune]

719
01:41:41,989 --> 01:41:43,991
- [door opens]
- [The Djinn] Gulten!

720
01:41:44,792 --> 01:41:46,694
[in Ottoman Turkish]

721
01:41:55,404 --> 01:41:57,072
[gasps]

722
01:42:12,987 --> 01:42:14,323
[whimpering]

723
01:42:16,991 --> 01:42:18,527
[The Djinn in English]
<i>"Make a wish!</i>

724
01:42:18,560 --> 01:42:20,862
"Save yourself, Gulten!"

725
01:42:21,963 --> 01:42:23,664
[panting]

726
01:42:25,100 --> 01:42:27,835
Just a few words
and she could have been free

727
01:42:27,869 --> 01:42:31,340
<i>to bear her child in safety,</i>

728
01:42:31,373 --> 01:42:35,077
<i>and I to spirit away at last
to the Realm of Djinn.</i>

729
01:42:35,110 --> 01:42:37,479
<i>But she ran into the hands
of the assassins.</i>

730
01:42:37,513 --> 01:42:39,181
- [Gulten screams]
- [The Djinn calls out]

731
01:42:39,214 --> 01:42:41,316
<i>I was about
to take them by force,</i>

732
01:42:41,350 --> 01:42:43,918
<i>when I was blocked
by a follower of Iblis.</i>

733
01:42:43,951 --> 01:42:46,954
- [breathing shakily]
- [high-pitched pinging]

734
01:42:52,727 --> 01:42:55,230
[in ancient language]

735
01:43:12,314 --> 01:43:14,183
[gasping]

736
01:43:17,619 --> 01:43:19,787
[creatures screeching]

737
01:43:19,820 --> 01:43:22,424
[grunting and whimpering]

738
01:43:24,092 --> 01:43:26,395
- [screeching stops]
- [gasping]

739
01:43:26,428 --> 01:43:27,429
Gulten!

740
01:43:43,445 --> 01:43:46,747
[in English] <i>She made</i>
<i>no wish to save herself.</i>

741
01:43:47,949 --> 01:43:50,918
<i>No wish was made
to save us both.</i>

742
01:43:54,755 --> 01:43:55,990
[sighs softly]

743
01:43:58,327 --> 01:44:00,128
So, there I was,

744
01:44:00,162 --> 01:44:02,264
or there I was not,
might you say,

745
01:44:02,297 --> 01:44:05,500
almost emancipated
and tethered to this world

746
01:44:05,534 --> 01:44:07,868
by a third wish unperformed.

747
01:44:07,902 --> 01:44:09,338
But you realize, don't you,

748
01:44:09,371 --> 01:44:12,541
that you've just told me the
story of a woman who was doomed

749
01:44:12,574 --> 01:44:14,610
as a consequence
of the wishes she made?

750
01:44:14,643 --> 01:44:17,479
Yes, but her failure
to complete the wishes

751
01:44:17,512 --> 01:44:19,581
also doomed me.

752
01:44:19,615 --> 01:44:21,717
Could nobody else
complete the wish?

753
01:44:21,749 --> 01:44:23,285
That was my hope.

754
