02:00:09,331 --> 02:00:10,599
Oh, you're impossible.

997
02:00:10,632 --> 02:00:12,568
And you are giving me
a headache.

998
02:00:12,601 --> 02:00:14,269
All right. All right.

999
02:00:14,303 --> 02:00:16,837
Here's what I'll do.
I will make three wishes.

1000
02:00:16,871 --> 02:00:17,972
- I will.
- Before you die?

1001
02:00:18,006 --> 02:00:19,774
Right now.
One after the other.

1002
02:00:19,807 --> 02:00:20,908
- Ready?
- Mmm-hmm.

1003
02:00:20,942 --> 02:00:23,844
Number one. I wish
your headache were gone.

1004
02:00:26,747 --> 02:00:28,483
Number two.

1005
02:00:28,517 --> 02:00:30,385
I wish for a sip of this tea.

1006
02:00:32,753 --> 02:00:35,756
And finally, I wish
for another one of those.

1007
02:00:35,790 --> 02:00:37,092
You mock me.

1008
02:00:37,125 --> 02:00:38,793
Three wishes, perfectly simple,

1009
02:00:38,826 --> 02:00:39,927
and theoretically safe.

1010
02:00:39,961 --> 02:00:41,996
I was imprisoned
by Solomon precisely

1011
02:00:42,030 --> 02:00:44,499
because I cried out
my heart's desire.

1012
02:00:44,533 --> 02:00:47,569
Only by granting you yours
may I earn my release.

1013
02:00:47,603 --> 02:00:49,204
Yes, well,
I appreciate the symmetry,

1014
02:00:49,238 --> 02:00:50,405
but the thing is this,

1015
02:00:50,439 --> 02:00:53,542
I cannot for the life of me
summon up one eligible wish.

1016
02:00:53,575 --> 02:00:54,842
And you're asking me for three.

1017
02:00:54,875 --> 02:00:57,312
Is there any life in you?
Are you even alive?

1018
02:00:57,346 --> 02:00:58,946
You know, in some cultures,

1019
02:00:58,980 --> 02:01:00,682
absence of desire
means enlightenment.

1020
02:01:00,716 --> 02:01:02,883
Then you are a pious fool.

1021
02:01:02,917 --> 02:01:05,354
If I'm content, why tempt fate?

1022
02:01:05,387 --> 02:01:06,588
And you're a coward.

1023
02:01:06,622 --> 02:01:07,955
Don't goad me.

1024
02:01:07,989 --> 02:01:09,924
There is no human,
no angel, nor djinn

1025
02:01:09,957 --> 02:01:11,169
that wouldn't grasp
at the chance

1026
02:01:11,193 --> 02:01:12,827
to fulfill
their deepest longings,

1027
02:01:12,860 --> 02:01:14,496
and I am saddled with the one

1028
02:01:14,529 --> 02:01:15,839
who claims to want
nothing at all.

1029
02:01:15,863 --> 02:01:17,332
Alithea Binnie,
you are a liar!

1030
02:01:17,366 --> 02:01:20,636
You know, I am beginning
to wish we never met.

1031
02:01:20,669 --> 02:01:22,170
No! <i>Nyet!</i>

1032
02:01:22,204 --> 02:01:23,338
Don't say that!

1033
02:01:23,372 --> 02:01:25,307
[heavy static buzzing]

1034
02:01:25,340 --> 02:01:27,942
[The Djinn panting]

1035
02:01:31,213 --> 02:01:33,948
- [static subsides]
- [Alithea breathing heavily]

1036
02:01:38,487 --> 02:01:39,554
[sniffling]

1037
02:01:39,588 --> 02:01:41,889
[glass shards clattering]

1038
02:01:48,963 --> 02:01:50,931
[The Djinn sighs]

1039
02:01:54,436 --> 02:01:55,437
So...

1040
02:01:56,871 --> 02:01:59,107
that's happened to you before.

1041
02:02:00,542 --> 02:02:02,377
And it was bad.

1042
02:02:02,411 --> 02:02:04,279
[clicks tongue] 'Twas bad.

1043
02:02:05,580 --> 02:02:07,582
'Twas bitter.

1044
02:02:07,616 --> 02:02:09,917
'Twas the cruelest wish of all.

1045
02:02:11,586 --> 02:02:14,656
[Alithea] You were undone
by silliness yet again.

1046
02:02:14,690 --> 02:02:16,091
[The Djinn sighs]

1047
02:02:16,124 --> 02:02:18,527
I'm here because of a genius.

1048
02:02:19,328 --> 02:02:20,928
Who was it this time?

1049
02:02:21,962 --> 02:02:23,532
She was Zefir.

1050
02:02:25,467 --> 02:02:29,471
Rarely among humankind
has there been such a wonder.

1051
02:02:30,439 --> 02:02:33,342
But you're here
because of her folly.

1052
02:02:34,343 --> 02:02:36,278
[tuts and sighs]

1053
02:02:36,311 --> 02:02:40,248
I ended up in this
as a consequence of Zefir.

1054
02:02:42,551 --> 02:02:43,719
And this is the story

1055
02:02:43,752 --> 02:02:46,987
you've been avoiding
telling me all along.

1056
02:02:47,022 --> 02:02:50,858
This is the story I've avoided
telling even myself.

1057
02:02:58,866 --> 02:03:02,671
[hooves clopping]

1058
02:03:02,704 --> 02:03:04,905
<i>Zefir was a foundling,</i>

1059
02:03:04,939 --> 02:03:07,609
<i>married at 12
to a wealthy merchant.</i>

1060
02:03:09,111 --> 02:03:11,279
<i>He was much older than her,
and kind,</i>

1061
02:03:11,313 --> 02:03:16,585
<i>if you think keeping someone
like a bird in a cage is kind.</i>

1062
02:03:16,618 --> 02:03:19,421
<i>There were two older wives,
who did not like her</i>

1063
02:03:19,454 --> 02:03:21,456
<i>and did not talk to her at all.</i>

1064
02:03:35,337 --> 02:03:38,106
[Zefir panting
and crying softly]

1065
02:03:39,207 --> 02:03:41,109
<i>Everyone,
including the servants,</i>

1066
02:03:41,143 --> 02:03:42,943
<i>seemed to be mocking her.</i>

1067
02:03:48,450 --> 02:03:49,584
[grunts]

1068
02:03:55,990 --> 02:03:59,027
<i>She had neither
etiquette nor learning.</i>

1069
02:03:59,060 --> 02:04:00,961
<i>She grew to no great beauty</i>

1070
02:04:00,995 --> 02:04:04,065
<i>and was angry
without knowing why.</i>

1071
02:04:04,800 --> 02:04:06,701
[panting]

1072
02:04:12,874 --> 02:04:14,476
[clangs]

1073
02:04:14,509 --> 02:04:16,545
[high-pitched pinging]

1074
02:04:18,313 --> 02:04:21,149
<i>As the fates would have it,
my bottle came to her</i>

1075
02:04:21,183 --> 02:04:24,619
<i>as a love token
from her husband.</i>

1076
02:04:29,558 --> 02:04:32,761
<i>And when she had finished
satisfying him</i>

1077
02:04:32,794 --> 02:04:34,062
<i>and was finally alone,</i>

1078
02:04:34,095 --> 02:04:36,331
<i>she managed to prise it open.</i>

1079
02:05:07,395 --> 02:05:10,031
<i>It was as if
she was waiting for me.</i>

1080
02:05:10,065 --> 02:05:13,168
<i>I saw at once
that she was sharp,</i>

1081
02:05:13,201 --> 02:05:17,038
<i>and she saw that I was desperate</i>

1082
02:05:17,072 --> 02:05:19,241
<i>for freedom and conversation.</i>

1083
02:05:19,274 --> 02:05:21,776
<i>I told her my story,
as I have told you,</i>

1084
02:05:21,810 --> 02:05:26,448
<i>and she revealed herself to me
by the things she had made.</i>

1085
02:05:26,481 --> 02:05:28,350
<i>Gel. Gel.</i>

1086
02:05:37,058 --> 02:05:38,693
[speaking Ottoman Turkish]

1087
02:05:56,211 --> 02:05:57,979
[speaks Ottoman Turkish]

1088
02:05:58,014 --> 02:05:59,214
[chuckles]

1089
02:06:00,482 --> 02:06:02,551
[continues speaking
Ottoman Turkish]

1090
02:06:03,685 --> 02:06:04,719
<i>Gel.</i>

1091
02:06:08,189 --> 02:06:10,125
[whispers indistinctly]

1092
02:06:15,564 --> 02:06:17,308
[The Djinn in English]
<i>She could have been remembered</i>

1093
02:06:17,332 --> 02:06:19,234
<i>like the genius da Vinci,</i>

1094
02:06:19,267 --> 02:06:20,535
<i>whose theories on flight</i>

1095
02:06:20,569 --> 02:06:23,338
<i>were the talk
of sultans and kings.</i>

1096
02:06:24,906 --> 02:06:28,510
<i>She was a skilled artist,
but no one saw her art.</i>

1097
02:06:29,177 --> 02:06:30,812
[Zefir breathing heavily]

1098
02:06:30,845 --> 02:06:34,516
[Zefir speaking Ottoman Turkish]

1099
02:06:34,549 --> 02:06:37,218
[The Djinn] <i>She told me</i>
<i>she was eaten up</i>

1100
02:06:37,252 --> 02:06:39,454
<i>with unused power.</i>

1101
02:06:39,487 --> 02:06:41,389
<i>She thought
she might be a witch.</i>

1102
02:06:42,390 --> 02:06:44,225
<i>Except, she said,
if she were a man,</i>

1103
02:06:44,259 --> 02:06:48,096
<i>her intellect would have been
ordinarily accepted.</i>

1104
02:06:48,129 --> 02:06:50,432
<i>She was a woman
ardent for learning,</i>

1105
02:06:50,465 --> 02:06:53,868
<i>and I knew
what her first wish would be.</i>

1106
02:06:53,902 --> 02:06:55,270
[pants]

1107
02:06:55,971 --> 02:06:57,372
[in Ottoman Turkish]

1108
02:07:08,183 --> 02:07:09,884
[breathing heavily]

1109
02:07:11,286 --> 02:07:12,897
[The Djinn in English]
<i>And it delighted me</i>

1110
02:07:12,921 --> 02:07:14,723
<i>to fulfill this wish.</i>

1111
02:07:21,463 --> 02:07:22,464
[sighs]

1112
02:07:26,368 --> 02:07:28,903
[pensive music playing]

1113
02:07:43,652 --> 02:07:47,222
<i>So, I taught her
histories, philosophies,</i>

1114
02:07:47,255 --> 02:07:48,623
<i>languages, poetry.</i>

1115
02:07:48,657 --> 02:07:51,326
<i>I taught her
astronomy, mathematic,</i>

1116
02:07:51,359 --> 02:07:53,495
<i>which was bliss to her.</i>

1117
02:07:53,528 --> 02:07:55,830
<i>I brought her
books and writings,</i>

1118
02:07:55,864 --> 02:07:59,567
<i>which we hid
in her collection of bottles.</i>

1119
02:08:20,022 --> 02:08:21,990
[The Djinn] <i>Sabah...</i>

1120
02:08:22,024 --> 02:08:23,491
[whispers] <i>Sabah...</i>

1121
02:08:23,525 --> 02:08:24,893
[squelching]

1122
02:08:24,926 --> 02:08:26,361
[Zefir gasps]

1123
02:08:37,906 --> 02:08:40,308
[speaking Ottoman Turkish]

1124
02:08:41,242 --> 02:08:43,244
<i>She could always
call on Aristotle</i>

1125
02:08:43,278 --> 02:08:45,413
<i>from a red glass jar,</i>

1126
02:08:45,447 --> 02:08:48,184
<i>or Euclid from a green,</i>

1127
02:08:48,216 --> 02:08:50,585
<i>Pythagoras, Spinoza,</i>

1128
02:08:50,618 --> 02:08:53,455
<i>without needing me
to re-embody them.</i>

1129
02:08:53,488 --> 02:08:56,725
[conversing in Ottoman Turkish]

1130
02:09:03,698 --> 02:09:06,068
We had the whole world
in her room,

1131
02:09:06,102 --> 02:09:09,270
and I lost my heart to her.

1132
02:09:11,573 --> 02:09:12,707
[gulps]

1133
02:09:12,741 --> 02:09:16,978
'Twas my bliss
to make her happy.

1134
02:09:18,813 --> 02:09:20,015
To see her flourish.

1135
02:09:21,683 --> 02:09:24,352
And she flourished in every way.

1136
02:09:24,786 --> 02:09:26,254
<i>Totalmente.</i>

1137
02:09:28,456 --> 02:09:31,326
[soft traditional music playing]

1138
02:09:37,233 --> 02:09:38,633
<i>She began to rebel</i>

1139
02:09:38,666 --> 02:09:40,902
<i>even against
the gestures of submission</i>

1140
02:09:40,935 --> 02:09:42,303
<i>that her husband required,</i>

1141
02:09:42,337 --> 02:09:45,507
<i>for she had acquired
a mastery of love-craft,</i>

1142
02:09:45,540 --> 02:09:47,143
<i>out of reach of any human</i>

1143
02:09:47,176 --> 02:09:49,511
<i>that had not
made love to a djinn.</i>

1144
02:09:50,678 --> 02:09:53,048
[surreal choral music playing]

1145
02:09:55,917 --> 02:09:57,919
[music distorts and fades]

1146
02:09:59,188 --> 02:10:02,457
[distorted screaming]

1147
02:10:04,093 --> 02:10:05,293
[Zefir grunting]

1148
02:10:05,326 --> 02:10:07,096
[Zefir's husband speaking
Ottoman Turkish]

1149
02:10:07,129 --> 02:10:10,365
[The Djinn] <i>His cravings</i>
<i>for her became an obsession.</i>

1150
02:10:10,398 --> 02:10:12,667
[in Ottoman Turkish]

1151
02:10:14,903 --> 02:10:15,904
[lock clicks]

1152
02:10:17,705 --> 02:10:18,907
[sighs]

1153
02:10:20,642 --> 02:10:22,319
[The Djinn in English]
<i>And when he would come to her,</i>

1154
02:10:22,343 --> 02:10:26,648
<i>I would leave her room
and journey the skies.</i>

1155
02:10:26,681 --> 02:10:30,552
<i>I saw the mountains,
the oceans...</i>

1156
02:10:31,386 --> 02:10:33,354
<i>I saw the beasts of the forest,</i>

1157
02:10:33,388 --> 02:10:35,890
<i>where no man treads.</i>

1158
02:10:35,924 --> 02:10:39,928
<i>And when I would return,
she would be waiting for me.</i>

1159
02:10:39,961 --> 02:10:44,066
<i>I would tell her of my day,
and she would faint with joy</i>

1160
02:10:44,099 --> 02:10:45,900
<i>and disappointment.</i>

1161
02:10:45,934 --> 02:10:49,470
[Alithea] <i>Why did she not</i>
<i>make a wish to be free?</i>

1162
02:10:49,504 --> 02:10:53,075
[The Djinn] <i>There was something</i>
<i>more important to her.</i>

1163
02:10:53,108 --> 02:10:55,376
<i>She had devised a "mathematica,"</i>

1164
02:10:55,410 --> 02:10:58,546
<i>a language to explain the forces</i>

1165
02:10:58,580 --> 02:11:01,649
<i>which bring space, and time,
and matter into being.</i>

1166
02:11:01,683 --> 02:11:03,351
<i>She was Promethean, brave.</i>

1167
02:11:03,384 --> 02:11:05,787
<i>But she could not solve
this puzzle.</i>

1168
02:11:05,820 --> 02:11:07,655
<i>She needed a key,</i>

1169
02:11:07,689 --> 02:11:10,825
<i>a key to open the doors
of her perception.</i>

1170
02:11:17,233 --> 02:11:18,600
[sobs]

1171
02:11:21,502 --> 02:11:25,406
So, she used her second wish.

1172
02:11:25,440 --> 02:11:29,111
I taught her to dream
as djinn do, awake.

1173
02:11:30,212 --> 02:11:32,947
[sentimental string
music playing]

1174
02:11:55,204 --> 02:11:57,405
[writing on paper]

1175
02:12:00,675 --> 02:12:04,579
<i>And this way,
the solutions came to her.</i>

1176
02:12:04,612 --> 02:12:08,284
<i>She was able
to explain powers invisible,</i>

1177
02:12:08,317 --> 02:12:11,519
electromagnetic fields
and forces...

1178
02:12:11,552 --> 02:12:14,656
The very stuff
of which djinn are made.

1179
02:12:14,689 --> 02:12:16,392
You're electromagnetic?

1180
02:12:16,424 --> 02:12:20,595
As you are dust,
I am made of subtle fire.

1181
02:12:21,363 --> 02:12:23,731
And when she was
to bear a child,

1182
02:12:23,765 --> 02:12:26,235
I was plagued with happiness,

1183
02:12:26,268 --> 02:12:28,337
for I knew
it would strengthen us.

1184
02:12:28,370 --> 02:12:30,005
She was carrying your child?

1185
02:12:30,705 --> 02:12:33,808
A child, of fire and dust.

1186
02:12:35,610 --> 02:12:37,612
So, where did it go wrong?

1187
02:12:37,645 --> 02:12:39,747
Alithea, I loved her.

1188
02:12:40,615 --> 02:12:42,318
I loved the fervor of her mind.

1189
02:12:42,351 --> 02:12:43,484
I loved her anger.

1190
02:12:43,518 --> 02:12:44,585
I loved my power

1191
02:12:44,619 --> 02:12:47,822
to turn her frowns into smiles.

1192
02:12:49,425 --> 02:12:52,061
I loved her more than Sheba.

1193
02:12:52,094 --> 02:12:53,628
More than your own freedom?

1194
02:12:53,661 --> 02:12:54,896
Yes.

1195
02:12:54,929 --> 02:12:58,434
It became my greatest desire
to... to keep her,

1196
02:12:58,499 --> 02:13:00,568
to remain her prisoner.

1197
02:13:00,601 --> 02:13:05,307
The thought of being set free
sickened my heart.

1198
02:13:05,341 --> 02:13:07,242
[speaking Ottoman Turkish]

1199
02:13:10,145 --> 02:13:14,482
I caught myself stopping her
lest she make her third wish.

1200
02:13:14,882 --> 02:13:16,218
Oh, gosh.

1201
02:13:19,954 --> 02:13:21,723
I made a mess of it.

1202
02:13:22,991 --> 02:13:25,994
<i>She began to accuse me
of trapping her,</i>

1203
02:13:26,028 --> 02:13:27,729
<i>- like her husband.</i>
- [Zefir sobbing]

1204
02:13:27,762 --> 02:13:29,764
[speaking Ottoman Turkish]

1205
02:13:29,797 --> 02:13:32,967
[The Djinn] <i>I tried</i>
<i>to make amends.</i>

1206
02:13:33,002 --> 02:13:36,771
<i>To atone, I would
put myself in the bottle.</i>

1207
02:13:37,572 --> 02:13:38,873
<i>To be sealed.</i>

1208
02:13:38,906 --> 02:13:41,676
<i>That way, she could have
more power over me.</i>

1209
02:13:42,510 --> 02:13:43,687
[The Djinn speaks indistinctly]

1210
02:13:43,711 --> 02:13:45,280
[Zefir continues sobbing]

1211
02:13:46,748 --> 02:13:47,791
[The Djinn whispers
indistinctly]

1212
02:13:47,815 --> 02:13:50,019
[Zefir speaking Ottoman Turkish]

1213
02:13:54,356 --> 02:13:57,092
To be nothing in a bottle.

1214
02:13:57,126 --> 02:13:58,693
I could do that for her.

1215
02:13:59,495 --> 02:14:03,265
And every time,
it would appease.

1216
02:14:03,298 --> 02:14:06,667
Every time, except for the last.

1217
02:14:06,701 --> 02:14:11,407
<i>When, like a sudden squall,
all thunder and lightning,</i>

1218
02:14:11,440 --> 02:14:14,443
<i>she began to weep and wail,
and said,</i>

1219
02:14:14,476 --> 02:14:17,545
<i>"I wish I could forget
I ever met you."</i>

1220
02:14:17,578 --> 02:14:19,348
[screams in Ottoman Turkish]

1221
02:14:19,381 --> 02:14:21,716
[gasping]

1222
02:14:23,218 --> 02:14:25,853
<i>And she did, on the instant.</i>

1223
02:14:30,825 --> 02:14:33,728
<i>She was out. I was in.</i>

1224
02:14:33,761 --> 02:14:35,630
<i>She'd forgotten me.</i>

1225
02:14:37,199 --> 02:14:40,135
<i>Alithea, how can it be...</i>

1226
02:14:42,037 --> 02:14:45,606
a mistake to love
someone entirely?

1227
02:15:11,033 --> 02:15:12,267
I have a wish.

1228
02:15:16,938 --> 02:15:20,275
However, I'm afraid it may be
too much to ask.

1229
02:15:24,812 --> 02:15:27,015
Is it within my power?

1230
02:15:27,549 --> 02:15:30,651
I hope so. I do hope so.

1231
02:15:33,288 --> 02:15:35,324
Is it your heart's desire?

1232
02:15:35,857 --> 02:15:38,026
Yeah, I'm certain of it.

1233
02:15:52,640 --> 02:15:54,042
See, erm,

1234
02:15:54,675 --> 02:15:57,045
I'm here to love you.

1235
02:15:59,981 --> 02:16:01,183
And, uh,

1236
02:16:02,584 --> 02:16:06,155
I wish for you
to love me in return.

1237
02:16:07,855 --> 02:16:10,825
You want us to make love-craft?

1238
02:16:11,360 --> 02:16:13,428
Yeah, that too.

1239
02:16:13,462 --> 02:16:14,530
All of it.

1240
02:16:14,563 --> 02:16:18,567
And you would
abandon yourself to this?

1241
02:16:18,600 --> 02:16:20,469
[low electrical humming]

1242
02:16:20,502 --> 02:16:22,171
Yes.

1243
02:16:22,204 --> 02:16:23,305
Yes.

1244
02:16:25,474 --> 02:16:29,244
I want our solitudes
to be together.

1245
02:16:29,278 --> 02:16:33,981
I want that love
professed in ageless tales.

1246
02:16:34,016 --> 02:16:38,320
I want that longing you felt
for the Queen of Sheba,

1247
02:16:38,353 --> 02:16:42,457
and that love you gave
to your genius, Zefir.

1248
02:16:42,491 --> 02:16:44,226
I want it.

1249
02:16:52,601 --> 02:16:55,870
[speaking Djinnbish]

1250
02:16:57,139 --> 02:16:58,407
Me?

1251
02:17:00,509 --> 02:17:01,909
You.

1252
02:17:04,246 --> 02:17:06,881
[speaking Djinnbish]

1253
02:17:08,617 --> 02:17:10,085
You?

1254
02:17:12,054 --> 02:17:13,222
Me.

1255
02:17:20,662 --> 02:17:22,130
Is it too much?

1256
02:17:23,065 --> 02:17:25,334
Is it all too much to ask?

1257
02:17:44,752 --> 02:17:45,953
[whispers] Come.

1258
02:17:59,101 --> 02:18:02,604
[Alithea] <i>What are we to do</i>
<i>with longings awoken?</i>

1259
02:18:02,638 --> 02:18:04,039
<i>How can I persuade you</i>

1260
02:18:04,072 --> 02:18:06,408
<i>that I once found love
with a djinn?</i>

1261
02:18:08,644 --> 02:18:11,480
<i>In any case,
few would believe me.</i>

1262
02:18:13,148 --> 02:18:16,817
<i>Love is not something
we come to by reason.</i>

1263
02:18:19,054 --> 02:18:21,323
<i>It's more like a vapor,</i>

1264
02:18:21,356 --> 02:18:23,258
<i>a dream, perhaps,</i>

1265
02:18:23,292 --> 02:18:25,427
<i>to lure us into the enchantment</i>

1266
02:18:25,460 --> 02:18:27,162
<i>of our own stories.</i>

1267
02:18:28,630 --> 02:18:30,265
<i>If that's so,</i>

1268
02:18:30,299 --> 02:18:32,501
<i>how are we to know
if it's ever real?</i>

1269
02:18:34,269 --> 02:18:37,972
<i>Is it a truth,
or simply a madness?</i>

1270
02:18:38,006 --> 02:18:40,575
[surreal folk music playing]

1271
02:18:49,418 --> 02:18:52,120
[people chattering
indistinctly from outside]

1272
02:19:01,596 --> 02:19:04,166
[takes deep breath]

1273
02:19:16,545 --> 02:19:18,547
[electric toothbrush whirring]

1274
02:19:23,585 --> 02:19:24,885
[switches off toothbrush]

1275
02:19:24,919 --> 02:19:27,456
[Alithea] I leave
for London today.

1276
02:19:27,489 --> 02:19:29,057
Will you come home with me?

1277
02:19:31,259 --> 02:19:34,162
It's not such
an easy place nowadays.

1278
02:19:35,197 --> 02:19:37,499
But it'll be better
if you're there.

1279
02:19:47,409 --> 02:19:49,611
- [metal detector beeping]
- Over here, please.

1280
02:19:51,346 --> 02:19:52,381
Hands up.

1281
02:19:55,450 --> 02:19:57,619
[body scanner whirring]

1282
02:20:00,756 --> 02:20:02,858
- Please step out.
- [body scanner beeping]

1283
02:20:02,890 --> 02:20:04,459
What is in your pockets?

1284
02:20:05,193 --> 02:20:06,194
Oh.

1285
02:20:07,095 --> 02:20:10,399
Uh, it's an empty bottle
and a top.

1286
02:20:11,500 --> 02:20:12,868
Please put it through X-ray.

1287
02:20:12,933 --> 02:20:13,934
It is very delicate,

1288
02:20:13,968 --> 02:20:15,246
and I don't want it
to get damaged.

1289
02:20:15,270 --> 02:20:17,239
It will not be damaged.
Please put through X-ray.

1290
02:20:17,272 --> 02:20:18,616
I would prefer that
it didn't go in the...

1291
02:20:18,640 --> 02:20:19,940
Passport. Boarding pass.

1292
02:20:21,309 --> 02:20:22,310
Thank you.

1293
02:20:32,754 --> 02:20:33,822
It's quite fragile.

1294
02:20:33,855 --> 02:20:35,123
[supervisor] Madam.

1295
02:20:39,428 --> 02:20:41,163
It's a saltshaker.

1296
02:20:48,770 --> 02:20:49,970
Oh.

1297
02:20:50,572 --> 02:20:52,707
No! No X-ray! Please!

1298
02:20:52,741 --> 02:20:54,942
Stop, madam, stop.

1299
02:21:05,620 --> 02:21:07,122
[speaks Turkish]

1300
02:21:11,493 --> 02:21:12,527
Madam.

1301
02:21:13,195 --> 02:21:14,196
Oh.

1302
02:21:39,087 --> 02:21:40,355
[keypad beeping]

1303
02:21:54,903 --> 02:21:56,438
In your own time.

1304
02:22:40,448 --> 02:22:42,784
[children chattering
and laughing]

1305
02:22:52,994 --> 02:22:55,196
[The Djinn]
The air is thick here.

1306
02:22:56,164 --> 02:23:00,368
Full of insistent voices
and rushing faces.

1307
02:23:00,902 --> 02:23:02,637
[Alithea] Oh?

1308
02:23:02,671 --> 02:23:05,240
Like Tiny Einstein?

1309
02:23:05,273 --> 02:23:07,609
Television, and phone towers,
and such?

1310
02:23:07,642 --> 02:23:09,144
Yes.

1311
02:23:09,177 --> 02:23:12,914
Yes. All your
ingenious devices

1312
02:23:12,948 --> 02:23:14,883
all murmuring at once.

1313
02:23:14,916 --> 02:23:16,785
Bend your head.

1314
02:23:16,818 --> 02:23:19,287
[high-pitched pinging]

1315
02:23:19,321 --> 02:23:21,590
[people clamoring
and traffic bustling]

1316
02:23:21,623 --> 02:23:23,491
- [gasps]
- [noises stop]

1317
02:23:23,525 --> 02:23:25,560
You hear all that?

1318
02:23:25,594 --> 02:23:27,063
[noises continue]

1319
02:23:27,095 --> 02:23:28,196
- [gasps]
- [noises stop]

1320
02:23:28,229 --> 02:23:31,199
I also see it and feel it.

1321
02:23:31,232 --> 02:23:34,202
I am a transmitter. [Chuckles]

1322
02:23:34,235 --> 02:23:36,137
Isn't it all too much?

1323
02:23:37,172 --> 02:23:38,607
I am a djinn.

1324
02:23:38,640 --> 02:23:39,741
I can adapt.

1325
02:23:41,743 --> 02:23:43,311
I'll soon get used to it.

1326
02:23:43,345 --> 02:23:45,180
[woman] She's back.

1327
02:23:45,213 --> 02:23:46,715
I believe she's back.

1328
02:23:46,748 --> 02:23:48,483
Is she with someone?

1329
02:23:48,516 --> 02:23:50,719
[woman] No, I think she's
talking to herself again.

1330
02:23:50,752 --> 02:23:52,287
[Alithea] Hello, Clementine.

1331
02:23:52,320 --> 02:23:54,589
Fanny. Are you well?

1332
02:23:54,623 --> 02:23:56,424
[Clementine]
Did you have any trouble?

1333
02:23:56,458 --> 02:23:58,827
Trouble? What kind of trouble?

1334
02:23:58,860 --> 02:24:00,462
With your foreign friends.

1335
02:24:00,495 --> 02:24:02,364
Because we often ask ourselves,

1336
02:24:02,397 --> 02:24:04,866
"Why would Dr. Binnie waste
her time and intelligence"

1337
02:24:04,899 --> 02:24:07,769
"studying the ways of others
instead of upholding our own?"

1338
02:24:07,802 --> 02:24:10,472
Embarrassed by
our British culture, are we?

1339
02:24:10,505 --> 02:24:11,606
No. No.

1340
02:24:11,640 --> 02:24:14,175
I am rather more likely
to be embarrassed by anybody

1341
02:24:14,209 --> 02:24:16,711
reflexly frightened
of anybody different.

1342
02:24:16,745 --> 02:24:17,855
What exactly are you saying?

1343
02:24:17,879 --> 02:24:19,614
She's calling us bigots.

1344
02:24:19,648 --> 02:24:20,482
Your word, not mine.

1345
02:24:20,515 --> 02:24:21,592
[Clementine] You misunderstand.

1346
02:24:21,616 --> 02:24:23,151
- Oh?
- It's not how they look, dear.

1347
02:24:23,184 --> 02:24:24,629
It's how they live.
What they believe.

1348
02:24:24,653 --> 02:24:26,388
- What they eat.
- What are you on about?

1349
02:24:26,421 --> 02:24:28,223
Everywhere one goes, ethnics.

1350
02:24:28,256 --> 02:24:31,226
We are being overwhelmed,
and we're inviting our doom.

1351
02:24:31,259 --> 02:24:32,460
[Fanny] It's not natural.

1352
02:24:32,494 --> 02:24:34,696
Birds belong in the air.
Fish belong in the sea.

1353
02:24:34,729 --> 02:24:36,798
And that is how the good Lord
meant us to be.

1354
02:24:36,831 --> 02:24:39,035
You're just spouting rubbish
from start to finish.

1355
02:24:39,068 --> 02:24:40,602
It's science.
It's a scientific fact.

1356
02:24:40,635 --> 02:24:41,746
- It's a false analogy.
- [voices echoing]

1357
02:24:41,770 --> 02:24:44,106
I mean, animals do have
a natural habitat.

1358
02:24:44,140 --> 02:24:46,307
It's true,
but human beings are capable

1359
02:24:46,341 --> 02:24:48,443
of living in any environment
they bloody well choose.

1360
02:24:48,476 --> 02:24:49,687
- That's not a fact.
- [airplane engine humming]

1361
02:24:49,711 --> 02:24:51,312
- What are you saying?
- It's an opinion.

1362
02:24:51,346 --> 02:24:52,447
And you're wrong.

1363
02:24:52,480 --> 02:24:54,026
I'm not putting up
with any more of this.

1364
02:24:54,050 --> 02:24:56,251
Come away, Clem.
Let the crazy lady be.

1365
02:24:56,284 --> 02:24:57,962
We're never gonna get
any sense out of her.

1366
02:24:57,986 --> 02:25:00,588
[Alithea] You know, I've never
said this to you before.

1367
02:25:01,123 --> 02:25:03,525
But you're both pitiful.

1368
02:25:03,558 --> 02:25:04,926
Shut your cake hole! [Echoing]

1369
02:25:04,959 --> 02:25:07,462
Pea-brained and pitiful.

1370
02:25:08,030 --> 02:25:10,231
You, fuck face!

1371
02:25:10,265 --> 02:25:14,369
Stop your ivy growing
on our side of the wall!

1372
02:25:15,336 --> 02:25:17,472
Why do I let them get to me?

1373
02:25:17,505 --> 02:25:19,574
I should feel sorry for them.

1374
02:25:19,607 --> 02:25:22,977
But this is my home.
It's my sanctuary.

1375
02:25:23,012 --> 02:25:24,412
[inhaler hisses]

1376
02:25:24,446 --> 02:25:26,815
[Clementine and Fanny's
voices echoing]

1377
02:25:26,848 --> 02:25:29,250
- I could wish them... [grunts]
- [static buzzes]

1378
02:25:30,119 --> 02:25:32,320
That's not a wish, by the way.

1379
02:25:32,353 --> 02:25:33,722
- I know.
- [exhales heavily]

1380
02:25:33,755 --> 02:25:36,025
[Clementine and Fanny's voices
continue echoing]

1381
02:25:36,058 --> 02:25:39,227
[people chattering indistinctly
from transmissions]

1382
02:25:42,897 --> 02:25:45,067
[Alithea breathing heavily]

1383
02:25:45,101 --> 02:25:47,302
[transmissions fading]

1384
02:25:51,473 --> 02:25:54,375
[sentimental string
music playing]

1385
02:26:45,293 --> 02:26:48,363
[sentimental string
music continues]

1386
02:27:37,412 --> 02:27:38,780
[Alithea whispers] My djinn.

1387
02:27:39,681 --> 02:27:40,882
[The Djinn] How was your day?

1388
02:27:40,915 --> 02:27:43,285
[Alithea] Every listening ear
was yours.

1389
02:27:43,319 --> 02:27:46,088
Every voice, every scent,
and touch.

1390
02:27:46,121 --> 02:27:47,789
You were everywhere.

1391
02:27:53,095 --> 02:27:54,729
Back in a minute.

1392
02:28:13,648 --> 02:28:15,750
[Fanny] Whoever could that be
at this hour?

1393
02:28:15,783 --> 02:28:16,985
[Clementine]
It could be her.

1394
02:28:20,356 --> 02:28:23,424
Clem. Fanny.

1395
02:28:25,327 --> 02:28:27,929
Chickpeas, cloves, pistachio.

1396
02:28:29,631 --> 02:28:31,466
They melt in your mouth.

1397
02:28:49,318 --> 02:28:50,952
This is my friend.

1398
02:28:52,154 --> 02:28:53,988
He'll be staying for a while.

1399
02:28:54,956 --> 02:28:55,957
Hello.

1400
02:28:59,094 --> 02:29:00,795
- Hello.
- Hello.

1401
02:29:05,100 --> 02:29:06,668
[Alithea] <i>My Djinn told me,</i>

1402
02:29:06,701 --> 02:29:09,637
<i>when they come together
in the Realm of Djinn,</i>

1403
02:29:09,671 --> 02:29:11,572
<i>they tell each other stories.</i>

1404
02:29:12,640 --> 02:29:14,909
<i>Stories are like breath to them.</i>

1405
02:29:14,943 --> 02:29:15,977
<i>They make meaning.</i>

1406
02:29:17,979 --> 02:29:19,181
<i>"Yes," I said.</i>

1407
02:29:19,214 --> 02:29:20,982
<i>"That's just how
it is with us."</i>

1408
02:29:21,883 --> 02:29:23,618
<i>Each story we tell is a fragment</i>

1409
02:29:23,651 --> 02:29:26,188
<i>in an endless
shape-shifting mosaic.</i>

1410
02:29:27,622 --> 02:29:31,893
<i>And this small pebble,
like all stories, must end.</i>

1411
02:29:33,728 --> 02:29:37,032
<i>If it's about wishing,
it's a cautionary tale.</i>

1412
02:29:38,200 --> 02:29:41,136
<i>So, how will it go wrong?</i>

1413
02:29:41,170 --> 02:29:43,638
<i>Perhaps, it already has.</i>

1414
02:29:46,841 --> 02:29:49,311
Even though Truth
stood before them naked,

1415
02:29:49,345 --> 02:29:50,945
they turned their backs.

1416
02:29:50,979 --> 02:29:55,483
So, Truth moved to the side
and waited in the shadows.

1417
02:29:55,516 --> 02:29:56,951
<i>In the days that followed,</i>

1418
02:29:56,985 --> 02:30:00,621
<i>the Djinn would accompany
the narratologist to her work.</i>

1419
02:30:00,655 --> 02:30:02,024
<i>And when he wasn't with her,</i>

1420
02:30:02,057 --> 02:30:05,493
<i>he would go in eager
exploration of the world.</i>

1421
02:30:05,526 --> 02:30:08,230
[machine beeping]

1422
02:30:08,263 --> 02:30:11,532
[The Djinn] <i>Today I had</i>
<i>such a marvelous day.</i>

1423
02:30:12,700 --> 02:30:15,670
<i>I saw many things.</i>

1424
02:30:15,703 --> 02:30:19,807
<i>I watched a human look into
the living brain of another</i>

1425
02:30:19,841 --> 02:30:22,610
<i>and arrest a fatal bleeding.</i>

1426
02:30:27,149 --> 02:30:28,850
<i>I visited the Collider.</i>

1427
02:30:30,019 --> 02:30:34,622
<i>A vast gizmo which probed
the essence of matter.</i>

1428
02:30:37,625 --> 02:30:40,862
<i>And then I saw a dish,
a great dish</i>

1429
02:30:40,895 --> 02:30:44,699
<i>that listens to the whispers
of stars long dead.</i>

1430
02:30:46,934 --> 02:30:48,703
Humankind is...

1431
02:30:48,736 --> 02:30:50,772
is a wonder, Alithea.

1432
02:30:51,539 --> 02:30:53,941
I'm happy you think so.

1433
02:30:53,975 --> 02:30:57,046
All of this since I was
trapped in Zefir's bottle.

1434
02:30:57,079 --> 02:31:02,017
All these astonishments,
in less than 200 years.

1435
02:31:02,051 --> 02:31:03,818
Yes, but, I mean,

1436
02:31:03,851 --> 02:31:08,323
that's just engineering
and technology.

1437
02:31:08,357 --> 02:31:10,758
Despite all the whiz-bang,

1438
02:31:10,792 --> 02:31:13,028
we remain bewildered.

1439
02:31:15,830 --> 02:31:17,932
When we can't contain the chaos,

1440
02:31:19,567 --> 02:31:22,337
we are filled
with dread and panic,

1441
02:31:22,371 --> 02:31:24,440
and we turn on each other.

1442
02:31:24,473 --> 02:31:27,176
But of course, you are human.

1443
02:31:27,209 --> 02:31:29,244
That is your nature.

1444
02:31:31,480 --> 02:31:35,050
Yeah. So, the story
never changes.

1445
02:31:36,051 --> 02:31:38,520
Hate prevails.

1446
02:31:38,554 --> 02:31:43,258
It metastasizes
and outlives love.

1447
02:31:44,926 --> 02:31:47,595
I just want to talk about love.

1448
02:31:47,628 --> 02:31:51,632
Such a mess of
contradictions, all of you.

1449
02:31:51,666 --> 02:31:52,767
Thank you very much.

1450
02:31:52,800 --> 02:31:56,238
Humankind, what a conundrum.

1451
02:31:56,271 --> 02:31:58,806
You fumble around in the dark,

1452
02:31:58,840 --> 02:32:02,144
and yet, you herd your
intelligence to great effect.

1453
02:32:02,177 --> 02:32:03,579
It is quite a story.

1454
02:32:03,611 --> 02:32:04,846
[chuckles softly]

1455
02:32:04,879 --> 02:32:07,715
Cannot wait to see
where it goes.

1456
02:32:07,748 --> 02:32:09,817
Or how it might end.

1457
02:32:10,219 --> 02:32:11,719
That too.

1458
02:32:11,752 --> 02:32:15,690
A mortal will never know,
but a djinn might.

1459
02:32:15,723 --> 02:32:18,293
A djinn has all the time
in the world.

1460
02:32:20,462 --> 02:32:22,464
Aren't you the lucky one?

1461
02:32:22,498 --> 02:32:23,965
Maybe.

1462
02:32:24,866 --> 02:32:28,270
But you creatures
of dust have...

1463
02:32:28,303 --> 02:32:29,637
have managed to eclipse

1464
02:32:29,670 --> 02:32:33,175
the power and purpose
of djinn and angel.

1465
02:32:33,208 --> 02:32:35,377
You have no use for us.

1466
02:32:35,410 --> 02:32:36,588
Perhaps, we will wither and...

1467
02:32:36,612 --> 02:32:38,080
- And fade away?
- Yes.

1468
02:32:38,113 --> 02:32:40,549
Yeah. Well, that used
to be the subject

1469
02:32:40,582 --> 02:32:42,650
of all my lectures and papers.

1470
02:32:42,683 --> 02:32:44,086
I know.

1471
02:32:46,588 --> 02:32:48,423
And yet, here you are.

1472
02:32:50,225 --> 02:32:52,227
My impossible.

1473
02:32:54,229 --> 02:32:55,230
Yes.

1474
02:32:59,734 --> 02:33:01,036
[keypad beeping]

1475
02:33:01,069 --> 02:33:02,070
[door unlocks]

1476
02:33:07,543 --> 02:33:08,843
Hello?

1477
02:33:14,349 --> 02:33:15,917
I'm home!

1478
02:33:25,960 --> 02:33:27,162
Hello?

1479
02:33:46,747 --> 02:33:47,949
[switch clicks]

1480
02:33:53,288 --> 02:33:54,789
Djinn?

1481
02:33:58,694 --> 02:33:59,860
My love?

1482
02:33:59,894 --> 02:34:01,230
[Alithea gasps]

1483
02:34:04,099 --> 02:34:05,100
Djinn.

1484
02:34:06,301 --> 02:34:07,302
[switch clicks]

1485
02:34:09,371 --> 02:34:10,472
What's this?

1486
02:34:13,175 --> 02:34:14,942
Can you hear me?

1487
02:34:14,976 --> 02:34:17,312
Djinn, speak to me.

1488
02:34:17,346 --> 02:34:18,846
Try to speak to me.

1489
02:34:20,682 --> 02:34:22,984
I wish you to speak to me.

1490
02:34:24,253 --> 02:34:25,487
[cracking]

1491
02:34:25,520 --> 02:34:26,521
[crumbling]

1492
02:34:27,055 --> 02:34:28,056
Oh...

1493
02:34:29,391 --> 02:34:31,859
[breathes heavily and grunts]

1494
02:34:35,430 --> 02:34:37,065
[breathing raggedly]

1495
02:34:38,200 --> 02:34:40,835
[inhales deeply]

1496
02:34:40,868 --> 02:34:42,837
- [static buzzes]
- [gasps and clears throat]

1497
02:34:42,870 --> 02:34:44,872
[in distorted high voice]
I was sleeping.

1498
02:34:44,905 --> 02:34:47,242
[grunts] Sleeping.

1499
02:34:48,876 --> 02:34:50,978
Djinn don't sleep.

1500
02:34:51,013 --> 02:34:52,481
[The Djinn] Let's go for a walk.

1501
02:34:52,514 --> 02:34:53,749
A long, bracing walk.

1502
02:34:53,781 --> 02:34:55,317
I have prepared
something for us.

1503
02:34:55,350 --> 02:34:56,951
[in normal voice]
I have it all planned.

1504
02:34:56,984 --> 02:34:59,321
[breathlessly]
A wonderous night for us.

1505
02:34:59,354 --> 02:35:01,290
It will be amazing.

1506
02:35:01,323 --> 02:35:04,092
- The best time of our lives.
- Stop!

1507
02:35:04,126 --> 02:35:08,430
These electromagnetic fields,
I can push them from my head.

1508
02:35:08,463 --> 02:35:09,997
I can push them away.

1509
02:35:10,931 --> 02:35:12,334
We'll go for a picnic.

1510
02:35:12,367 --> 02:35:13,435
[panting]

1511
02:35:13,468 --> 02:35:15,803
[speaking Djinnbish]

1512
02:35:17,072 --> 02:35:19,408
Ah, we'll play the ukulele.

1513
02:35:19,441 --> 02:35:21,777
[speaking Djinnbish]

1514
02:35:21,809 --> 02:35:25,280
Alithea, there is a place
for me here.

1515
02:35:25,314 --> 02:35:26,248
These forces,

1516
02:35:26,281 --> 02:35:28,050
they will never go away,
not from this world.

1517
02:35:28,083 --> 02:35:30,252
I will overcome them.
I can do that for you.

1518
02:35:30,285 --> 02:35:32,421
You are my Alithea,
and I love you.

1519
02:35:32,454 --> 02:35:34,222
Thank you. Thank you.
Thank you for trying.

1520
02:35:34,256 --> 02:35:35,536
You don't think that I love you?

1521
02:35:36,658 --> 02:35:38,660
Love is a gift.

1522
02:35:38,694 --> 02:35:41,063
It's a gift of oneself
given freely.

1523
02:35:41,096 --> 02:35:43,432
It's not something
one can ever ask for.

1524
02:35:44,832 --> 02:35:46,034
I tricked us both.

1525
02:35:46,068 --> 02:35:47,736
The moment I spoke that wish,

1526
02:35:47,769 --> 02:35:50,838
I took away
your power to grant it.

1527
02:35:50,871 --> 02:35:55,077
I, more than anybody,
I should've known that.

1528
02:35:55,110 --> 02:35:57,245
I'm not going
to screw this up again.

1529
02:35:57,279 --> 02:36:01,416
My Djinn, if this world
is not for you,

1530
02:36:01,450 --> 02:36:04,453
I wish that you return
to where you belong.

1531
02:36:05,354 --> 02:36:07,356
Wherever that may be.

1532
02:36:10,058 --> 02:36:11,593
[breathing heavily]

1533
02:36:11,626 --> 02:36:14,162
[glass cracking]

1534
02:36:19,801 --> 02:36:22,003
[shuddering]

1535
02:36:27,509 --> 02:36:28,909
[sobs]

1536
02:37:23,865 --> 02:37:25,167
[switch clicks]

1537
02:37:34,676 --> 02:37:35,677
[sighs]

1538
02:37:41,116 --> 02:37:44,319
[emotional string music playing]

1539
02:38:03,805 --> 02:38:06,341
[couple laughing]

1540
02:38:19,921 --> 02:38:22,157
[couple speaking indistinctly]

1541
02:38:34,736 --> 02:38:35,737
[girl] Mommy!

1542
02:38:37,806 --> 02:38:39,808
[man] Come here, little monkey.

1543
02:38:39,841 --> 02:38:41,443
That's not Mommy.

1544
02:38:41,476 --> 02:38:43,678
[girl and man
speaking indistinctly]

1545
02:39:16,511 --> 02:39:18,213
[dog barks]

1546
02:39:18,246 --> 02:39:20,048
[kids shouting playfully]

1547
02:39:23,818 --> 02:39:25,520
[wind blows]

1548
02:39:39,801 --> 02:39:43,772
[mouthing]

1549
02:39:50,745 --> 02:39:52,614
[wind whistling]

1550
02:39:55,216 --> 02:39:58,486
[sentimental string
music playing]

1551
02:40:09,230 --> 02:40:10,441
[man 1] Hey, hey, hey!
[man 2] Ah, no!

1552
02:40:10,465 --> 02:40:12,634
[man 1] Watch it.
Top striker in the league.

1553
02:40:20,108 --> 02:40:21,610
- [grunts]
- [men laughing]

1554
02:40:21,643 --> 02:40:23,111
[man 1] Did you see that?

1555
02:40:26,114 --> 02:40:28,683
[Alithea] <i>He would visit</i>
<i>from time to time,</i>

1556
02:40:28,717 --> 02:40:32,187
<i>and they would grasp
each vivid moment.</i>

1557
02:40:32,220 --> 02:40:35,123
<i>Despite the pain
of the raucous skies,</i>

1558
02:40:35,156 --> 02:40:37,926
<i>he always stayed
longer than he should,</i>

1559
02:40:37,959 --> 02:40:40,261
<i>long after
she begged him to leave.</i>

1560
02:40:41,262 --> 02:40:44,432
<i>He promised to return
in her lifetime,</i>

1561
02:40:44,466 --> 02:40:47,602
<i>and for her,
that was more than enough.</i>

1562
02:40:49,337 --> 02:40:52,507
[sentimental string
music continues]


